\id 1CH Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h 1 Paralipomenon
\mt1 The First Book of Paralipomenon.
In Hebrew, Dibre Haiamim. דברי הימים
\c 1
\p
\v 1 Adam, Seth, Enos, \f + \fr 1:1 \ft Adam had two other sons before Seth, but Cain's race was utterly extinguished by the flood, and Abel had no children.\f*
\v 2 Cainan, Malaleel, Jared,
\v 3 Henoch, Mathusale, Lamech,
\v 4 Noe, Sem, Cham, and Japheth.
\v 5 The sons of Japheth: Gomer, and Magog, & Madai, and Javan, Thubal, Mosoch, Thiras.
\v 6 Moreover the sons of Gomer: Ascenez, and Riphath, and Thogorma.
\v 7 And the sons of Javan: Elisa and Tharsis, Cethim and Dodanim.
\v 8 The sons of Cham: Chus, and Mesraim, and Phut, and Chanaan.
\v 9 And the sons of Chus: Saba, and Hevila, Sabatha, and Regma, and Sabathaca. Moreover the sons of Regma: Saba, and Dadan.
\v 10 And Chus begat Nemrod: this began to be mighty in the earth.
\v 11 But Mesraim begat Ludim, and Anamim, and Laabim, and Nephtuim,
\v 12 Phetrusim also, and Casluim: from whom came Philisthiim, & Caphthorim.
\v 13 But Chanaan begat Sidon his firstborn, the Hetheite also,
\v 14 and the Jebuseite, and the Amorrhite, and the Gergesite,
\v 15 & the Heveite, & the Aracite, & the Sinite.
\v 16 The Aradium also, and the Samarite, & the Hamathite.
\v 17 The sons of Sem: Ælam, and Assur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and Aram, & Hus, and Hul, and Gether, and Mosoch.
\v 18 And Arphaxad begat Sale, who also begat Heber.
\v 19 Moreover to Heber were born two sons, the name of one was Phaleg, because in his days the earth was divided; and the name of his brother Jectan.
\v 20 And Jectan begat Elmodad, & Saleph, and Asarmoth, and Jare,
\v 21 Adoram also, and Usal, and Decla,
\v 22 Hebal also, and Abimael, and Saba, moreover
\v 23 also Ophir, and Hevila, and Jobab. All these are the sons of Jectan:
\v 24 Sem, Arphaxad, Sale,
\v 25 Heber, Phaleg, Ragau,
\v 26 Serug, Nachor, Thare,
\v 27 Abram, this is Abraham. \f + \fr 1:27 \ft As before the right line of Adam to Noe, so here from his son Sem to Abram. For mystery sake God changed his name to Abraham. Gen. 17.\f*
\v 28 And the sons of Abraham, Isaac and Ismael.
\v 29 And these are the generations of them. The first-begotten of Ismael, Nabajoth, and Cedar, and Adbeel, and Mabsam,
\v 30 and Masma, and Duma, Massa, Hadad, and Thema,
\v 31 Jetur, Naphis, Cedma. These are the sons of Ismahel.
\v 32 And the sons of Cetura Abraham's concubine, which she bare: Zamran, Jecsan, Madan, Madian, Jesboc, and Sue. Moreover the sons of Jecsan: Saba, and Dadan. And the sons of Dadan: Assurim, and Latussim, and Laomim.
\v 33 And the sons of Madian: Epha, and Epher, and Henoch, and Abida, and Eldaa. All these the sons of Cetura.
\v 34 And Abraham begat Isaac: whose sons were Esau, and Israel.
\v 35 The sons of Esau: Eliphaz, Rahuel, Jehus, Ihelom, and Core.
\v 36 The sons of Eliphaz: Theman, Omar, Sephi, Gathan, Cenez, Thamna, Amalec.
\v 37 The sons of Rahuel: Nahath, Zaza, Samma, Meza.
\v 38 The sons of Seir: Lotan, Sobal, Sebeon, Ana, Dison, Eser, Disan.
\v 39 The sons of Lotan: Hori, Homam. And the sister of Lotan was Thamna.
\v 40 The sons of Sobal: Alian, and Manahath, and Ebal, Sephi, and Onam. The sons of Sebeon: Aia and Ana. The sons of Ana: Dison.
\v 41 The sons of Dison: Hamram, and Eseban, and Jethran, and Charan.
\v 42 The sons of Eser: Balaan, and Zavan, and Jacan. The sons of Disan: Hus and Aran.
\v 43 These be the kings, that reigned in the Land of Edom, before there was a king over the children of Israel: Bale the son of Beor: and the name of his city, Denaba.
\v 44 And Bale died, and Jobab the son of Zare of Bosra, reigned for him.
\v 45 And when Jobab also was dead, Husam of the Land of the Themanes reigned for him.
\v 46 And Husam also died, and Adad the son of Badad reigned for him, who struck Madian in the Land of Moab: and the name of his city was Avith.
\v 47 And when Adad also was dead, Semla of Masreca reigned for him.
\v 48 But Semla also died, and there reigned for him Saul of Rohoboth, which is situate besides the river.
\v 49 Saul also being dead, Balanan, the son of Achobor reigned for him.
\v 50 But this also died, and Adad reigned for him: whose city's name was Phau, and his wife was called Meetabel the daughter of Matred, the daughter of Mezaab.
\v 51 And Adad being dead, there began to be dukes in Edom for kings: duke Thamna, duke Alva, duke Jetheth,
\v 52 duke Oolibama, duke Ela, duke Phinon,
\v 53 duke Cenez, duke Theman, duke Mabsar,
\v 54 duke Magdiel, duke Hiram. These be the dukes of Edom.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 And the children of Israel: Ruben, Simeon, Levi, Juda, Issachar, and Zabulon, \f + \fr 2:1 \ft This Patriarch first called Jacob signifying supplanter, was afterward called Israel, that is, Seeing God, or valiant with God. Gen. 35.\f*
\v 2 Dan, Joseph, Benjamin, Nephthali, Gad, and Aser.
\v 3 The sons of Juda: Her, Onan, and Sela, these three were born to him of the Chananite the daughter of Sue. And Her the first-begotten of Juda, was evil before our Lord, & he slew him.
\v 4 And Thamar his daughter in law bare him Phares and Zara.
\v 5 Therefore all the sons of Juda, were five. And the sons of Phares, Hesron and Hamul.
\v 6 The sons also of Zara: Zamri, & Ethan, and Eman, Chalcal also, and Dara, together five.
\v 7 And the sons of Charmi: Achar, who troubled Israel, and sinned in the theft of the anathema. \f + \fr 2:7 \ft Either this man had two names, or there is error in the last letter, here, or Iosue 7.\f*
\v 8 The sons of Ethan: Azarias.
\v 9 And the sons of Hesron that were born to him: Jerameel, & Ram, & Calubi.
\v 10 Moreover Ram begat Aminadab, & Aminadab begat Nahasson, the Prince of the children of Juda.
\v 11 Nahasson also begat Salma, of whom was born Booz.
\v 12 But Booz begat Obed, who also begat Isai.
\v 13 And Isai begat the first-begotten Eliab, the second Abinadab, the third Simmaa,
\v 14 the fourth, Nathanael, the fifth Raddai,
\v 15 the sixth Asom, the seventh David.
\v 16 Whose sisters were Sarvia, & Abigail. The sons of Sarvia: Abisai, Joab, and Asael, three.
\v 17 And Abigail bear Amasa, whose father was Jether the Ismaelite.
\v 18 But Caleb the son of Hesron took a wife named Azuba, of whom he begat Jerioth: and her sons were Jaser, and Sobab, and Ardon. \f + \fr 2:18 \ft Otherwise called Calubi. v. 9.\f*
\v 19 And when Azuba was dead, Caleb took to wife Ephratha: who bare him Hur.
\v 20 Moreover Hur begat Uri, and Uri begat Bezeleel.
\v 21 After these things Hesron went in to the daughter of Machir the father of Galaad, & took her, when he was threescore years old: who bare him Segub.
\v 22 But Segub also begat Jair, and possessed three and twenty cities in the Land of Galaad.
\v 23 And he took Gessur, and Aram, the towns of Jair, and Canath, and the villages thereof, threescore cities, all these are the sons of Machir the father of Galaad. \f + \fr 2:23 \ft By sons, as often elsewhere, are understood nephews & other offspring.\f*
\v 24 And when Hesron was dead, Caleb went into Ephrata. Hesron also had to wife, Abia, who bare him Ashur the father of Thecua.
\v 25 And there were born sons to Jerameel, the first-begotten of Hesron, Ram his first-born, and Buna, and Aram, and Asom, and Achia.
\v 26 Jerameel married also another wife, named Atara, which was the mother of Onam.
\v 27 But the sons also of Ram the first-begotten of Jerameel, were Moos, Jamin, and Acar.
\v 28 And Onam had sons Semei, & Jada. And the sons of Semei: Nadab, and Abisur:
\v 29 But the name of Abisur's wife, was Abihail, who bare him Ahobban, & Molid.
\v 30 And the sons of Nadab were Saled, and Apphaim. And Saled died without children.
\v 31 But the son of Apphaim, Jesi: which Jesi begat Sesan. Moreover Sesan begat Oholai.
\v 32 And the sons of Jada the brother of Semei: Jether, and Jonathan. But Jether also died without children.
\v 33 Moreover Jonathan begat Phaleth, and Ziza. These were the sons of Jerameel.
\v 34 And Sesan had no sons, but daughters: and a servant an Ægyptian, named Jeraa.
\v 35 And he gave him his daughter to wife: who bare him Ethei.
\v 36 And Ethei begat Nathan, and Nathan begat Zabad,
\v 37 Zabad also begat Ophlal, and Ophlal begat Obed.
\v 38 Obed begat Jehu, Jehu begat Azarias,
\v 39 Azarias begat Helles, and Helles begat Elasa,
\v 40 Elasa begat Sisamoi, Sisamoi begat Sellum,
\v 41 Sellum begat Icamia, and Icamia begat Elisama.
\v 42 And the sons of Caleb the brother of Jerameel: Mesa his first-begotten, he is the father of Ziph: & the sons of Maresa the father of Hebron.
\v 43 Moreover the sons of Hebron, Core, and Thaphua, and Recem, and Samma.
\v 44 And Samma begat Raham, the father of Jercaam, and Recem begat Sammai.
\v 45 The son of Sammai, Maon: and Maon the father of Bethsur.
\v 46 And Epha the concubine of Caleb bare Haran, and Mosa, and Gezez. Moreover Haran begat Gezez.
\v 47 And the sons of Jahaddai, Regom, and Joathan, and Gesan, and Phalet, and Epha, and Saaph.
\v 48 The concubine of Caleb Maacha bare Saber, and Tharana.
\v 49 And Saaph the father of Madmena begat Sue the father of Machbena, and the father of Gabaa. But the daughter of Caleb, was Achsa.
\v 50 These were the sons of Caleb the son of Hur the first-begotten of Ephrata, Sobal the father of Cariathiarim.
\v 51 Salma the father of Bethlehem, Hariph the father of Bethgader.
\v 52 And there were sons of Sobal the father of Chariathiarim, he that saw the half of the restings. \f + \fr 2:52 \ft * dwellings, or resting places.\f*
\v 53 And of the kindred of Cariathiarim, the Jethrites, and Aphuthites, and Semathites, and Maseretes. Out of these issued the Saraites, and Esthaolites.
\v 54 The sons of Salma, Bethlehem, and Netophathi, the Crowns of the house of Joab, and the Half of the resting of Sarai. \f + \fr 2:54 \ft Valiant men by whose help Joab got victories and triumphant crowns.\f*
\v 55 The kindreds also of the scribes dwelling in Jabes, singing and sounding, and abiding in tabernacles. These are the Cineites, which came from Heate of the father of the house of Rechab.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 But David had these sons, which were born to him in Hebron: the first begotten Amnon of Achinoam the Jesraelite, the second Daniel of Abigail the Carmelite,
\v 2 the third Absalom the son of Maacha the daughter of Tolmai the king of Gessur, the fourth Adonias the son of Aggith,
\v 3 the fifth Saphatias of Abital, the sixth Jethraham of Egla his wife.
\v 4 Six sons therefore were born to him in Hebron, where he reigned seven years and six months. And in Jerusalem he reigned three and thirty years.
\v 5 Moreover in Jerusalem sons were born to him, Simmaa, and Sobab, and Nathan, and Salomon, four of Bethsabee the daughter of Ammiel,
\v 6 Jebaar also and Elisama,
\v 7 and Eliphaleth, and Noge, and Nepheg, and Japhia,
\v 8 moreover Elisama, and Eliada, and Elipheleth, nine:
\v 9 all these the sons of David, beside the sons of his concubines: and they had a sister Thamar.
\v 10 And the son of Salomon, Roboam: whose son Abia begat Asa. Of this also was born Josaphat,
\v 11 the father of Joram: which Joram begat Ochozias, of whom rose Joas:
\v 12 and his son Amasias begat Azarias. Moreover Azarias the son of Joathan
\v 13 begat Achaz, the father of Ezechias, of whom was born Manasses.
\v 14 But Manasses also begat Amon the father of Josias.
\v 15 And the sons of Josias were, the firstbegotten Johanam, the second Joakim, the third Sedecias, the fourth Sellum. \f + \fr 3:15 \ft S. Matthew omitteth this Joakim, and counteth Jechonias as the son of Josias. The same Jechonias was also otherwise called Joachin, 4. Reg. 24. v. 6. & 25. v. 27. S. Hierom. li. 1. in Matth.\f*
\v 16 Of Joakim was born Jechonias, and Sedecias.
\v 17 The sons of Jechonias were Asir, Salathiel,
\v 18 Melchiram, Phadaia, Senneser and Jecemia, Sama, and Nadabia.
\v 19 Of Phadaia were born Zorobabel and Semei. Zorobabel begat Mosollom, Hananias, and Salomith their sister:
\v 20 Hasaba also, and Ohol, and Barachias, and Hasadias, Josabhesed, five.
\v 21 And the son of Hananias, Phaltias the father of Jeseias, whose son was Raphaia. This man's son also Arnan, of whom was born Obdia, whose son was Sechenias.
\v 22 The son of Sechenias: Semeia, whose sons were Hattus, and Jegaal, and Baria, and Naaria, & Saphat, six in number. \f + \fr 3:22 \ft Semeia with his five sons are counted six sons of Sechenias, though Semeia only was his proper son, the other his nephews. See annotation. ch. 1. num. 3.\f*
\v 23 The sons of Naaria, Elioenai, and Ezechias, and Ezricam, three.
\v 24 The sons of Elioenai, Oduia, and Eliasub, & Pheleia, and Accub, and Johanan, and Dalaia, and Anani, seven.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 The sons of Juda: Phares, Hesron, and Charmi, and Hur, and Sobal.
\v 2 But Raia the son of Sobal begat Jahath, of whom were born Ahumai, and Laad. These be the kindreds of Sarathi.
\v 3 This also is the stock of Etam: Jezrahel, and Jesema, and Jedebos. And the name of their sister Asalelphuni.
\v 4 And Phanuel the father of Gedor, and Ezar the father of Hosa, these are the sons of Hur the first begotten of Ephratha the father of Bethlehem.
\v 5 But Assur the father of Thecua had two wives, Halaa, and Naara.
\v 6 And Naara bare him Oozam, and Hepher, and Themani, & Ahasthari. These are the sons of Naara.
\v 7 Moreover the sons of Halaa, Sereth, Isaar, and Ethnan.
\v 8 And Cos begat Anob, and Soboba, and the kindred of Aharehel the son of Arum.
\v 9 And Jabes was honorable above his brethren, and his mother called his name Jabes, saying: Because I bare him in sorrow.
\v 10 But Jabes invocated the God of Israel, saying: If blessing thou wilt bless me, and wilt enlarge my borders, and thy hand be with me, and thou wilt make that I be not oppressed by malice. And God granted the things that he prayed for. \f + \fr 4:10 \ft In joining a vow to his prayer he imitated holy Jacob. Gen. 28. And they both desired temporal things for the better serving of God, & advancing his glory; especially that they might be assisted with grace not to yield to tentations, nor sin of malice.\f*
\v 11 And Caleb the brother of Sua begat Mahir, who was the father of Esthon.
\v 12 Moreover Esthon begat Bethrapha, and Phesse, and Tehinna the father of the city of Naas: these are the men of Recha.
\v 13 And the sons of Cenez, Othoniel, and Saraia. Moreover the sons of Othoniel, Hathath, and Maonathi.
\v 14 Maonathi begat Ophra, and Saraia begat Joab the father of the Vale of Artificers: for there were artificers. \f + \fr 4:14 \ft Chief lord of the valley; where the artificers dwelt that made the Temple.\f*
\v 15 And the sons of Caleb the son of Jephone, Hir, & Ela, and Naham. The sons also of Ela: Cenez.
\v 16 The sons also of Jaleleel: Ziph, and Zipha, Thiria, and Asrael.
\v 17 And the sons of Esra, Jether, and Mered, and Epher, and Jalon, and he begat Mariam, and Sammai, and Jesba the father of Esthamo.
\v 18 Also his wife Judaia, bare Jared the father of Gedor, and Heber the father of Socho, and Icuthiel the father of Zanoe. And these are the sons of Bethia the daughter of Pharao, whom Mered took.
\v 19 And the sons of the wife of Odaia the sister of Naham the father of Ceila, Garmi, and Esthamo, which was of Macathi.
\v 20 The sons also Simon, Amnon, and Rinna the son of Hanan, and Thilon. And the sons of Jesi, Zoheth, and Benzoheth.
\v 21 The sons of Sela the son of Juda: Her the father of Lecha, and Laada the father of Maresa, and the kindreds of their house that work silk in the House of oath.
\v 22 And he that made the Sun to stand, and the men of Lying, and Secure, and Burning, which were Princes in Moab, & which returned into Lahem. And these are old words.
\v 23 These are potters, dwelling in Plantings, and in Hedges, with the king in his works, and they abode there.
\v 24 The sons of Simeon: Namuel, and Jamin, Jarib, Zara, Saul:
\v 25 Sellum his son, Mapsam his son, Masma his son.
\v 26 The sons of Masma: Hamuel his son, Zachur his son, Semei his son.
\v 27 The sons of Semei sixteen, and six daughters: but his brethren had not many sons, and the whole kindred could not reach to the sum of the children of Juda.
\v 28 And they dwelt in Bersabee, and Molada, and Hasarsuhal,
\v 29 and in Bala, and in Asom, and in Tholad,
\v 30 and in Bathuel, and in Hormi, and in Siceleg,
\v 31 and in Bethmarcaboth, and in Hasarsusim, and in Bethberai, and in Saarim. These were their cities until king David.
\v 32 Their towns also: Etam, & Æn, Rhemmon, and Thochen, and Asan, five cities.
\v 33 And all their villages round about these cities unto Baal. This is their habitation, and the distribution of their dwellings.
\v 34 Mosabab also and Jemlech, and Josa the son of Amasias,
\v 35 and Joel, & Jehu the son of Josabia, the son of Saraia, the son of Asiel.
\v 36 and Elioenai, & Jacoba, & Isuhaia, & Asaia, & Adiel, and Ismiel, & Banaia,
\v 37 Ziza also the son of Zephei the son of Allon the son of Adaia, the son of Semri the son of Samaia.
\v 38 These renowned Princes in their kindreds, and in the house of their affinities they were multiplied exceedingly.
\v 39 And they went forth to enter into Gador as far as the East side of the valley, and to seek pastures for their flocks.
\v 40 And they found fat pastures, and very good, and a country very large and quiet and fruitful, in the which before had dwelt the stock of Cham.
\v 41 These therefore, whom before we described by name, came in the days of Ezechias the king of Juda: and they struck their tabernacles, and the inhabitants that were found there, & clean destroyed them until this present day: and they dwelt for them, because they found there most fat pastures.
\v 42 Also of the children of Simeon there went into mount Seir five hundred men, having their Princes Phaltias and Naaria and Raphaia and Oziel the sons of Jesi:
\v 43 and they struck the remnant of the Amalecites, which were able to escape, and they dwelt there for them until this day.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Also the sons of Ruben the first-begotten of Israel (for he was his first-begotten: but when he had violated his father's bed, his first-birth-right was given to the sons of Joseph the son of Israel, and he was not reputed for the first-begotten. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft See annotations; Gen. 49. nu. 4.\f*
\v 2 Moreover Judas, which was the strongest among his brethren, of his stock sprang the Princes: but the first-birth-right was reputed to Joseph.)
\v 3 The sons then of Ruben the first-begotten of Israel: Enoch, and Phallu, Esron, and Charmi.
\v 4 The sons of Joel: Samia his son, Gog his son, Semei his son.
\v 5 Micha his son, Reia his son, Baal his son,
\v 6 Beera his son, whom Theglathphalnasar the king of the Assyrians led away captive, and he was Prince in the tribe of Ruben.
\v 7 And his brethren, and all his kindred, when they were numbered by their families, had these Princes Jehiel, and Zacharias.
\v 8 Moreover Bala the son of Azaz, the son of Samma, the son of Joel, he dwelt in Aroer as far as Nebo, and Beelmeon.
\v 9 Against the east quarter also he dwelt unto the entrance of the desert, and the river Euphrates. For they possessed a great number of cattle in the land of Galaad.
\v 10 And in the days of Saul they fought against the Agarenes, and slew them, and dwelt for them in their tabernacles, in all the quarter, that looketh to the East of Galaad.
\v 11 But the children of Gad dwelt over-against them in the land of Basan, as far as Selcha:
\v 12 Johel the head, and Sapham the second: and Janai, & Saphat in Basan.
\v 13 And their brethren according to the houses of their kindreds, Michael, and Mosollam, and Sebe, and Jorai, and Jacan, and Zie, & Heber, seven.
\v 14 These are the sons of Abihail, the son of Huri, the son of Jara, the son of Galaad, the son of Michael, the son of Jesesi, the son of Jeddo, the son of Buz.
\v 15 Also the brethren of the son of Abdiel, the son of Guni, prince of the house in their families.
\v 16 And they dwelt in Galaad, and in Basan, and in the towns thereof, and in all the suburbs of Saron, unto the borders.
\v 17 All these were numbered in the days of Joathan the king of Juda, and in the days of Jeroboam the king of Israel.
\v 18 The children of Ruben, and of Gad, and the half tribe of Manasses, men of war, carrying shields, and swords, and bending the bow, and taught to battles, four and forty thousand and seven hundred threescore going forth to fight.
\v 19 They fought against the Agarenes, but the Itureians, and Naphis, and Nodab
\v 20 gave them aid. And the Agarenes were delivered into their hands, and all that were with them, because they called upon God when they fought: and he heard them, because they believed in him. \f + \fr 5:20 \ft Of these and the like, S. Paul saith: By faith they\f*
\v 21 And they took all that they possessed, Camels fifty thousand, and sheep two hundred fifty thousand, and asses two thousand, and of men an hundred thousand souls.
\v 22 And many fell down wounded: for it was the battle of our Lord. And they dwelt for them until the transmigration.
\v 23 Also the children of the half tribe of Manasses possessed the land, from the coasts of Basan unto Baal, Hermon, and Sanir, & mount Hermon, for the number was great.
\v 24 And these were the Princes of the house of their kindred, Epher, & Jesi, and Eliel, & Esriel, and Jeremia, and Odoia, and Jediel, most valiant men and mighty, & renowned Princes in their families.
\v 25 But they forsook the God of their fathers, and fornicated after the gods of the peoples of the land, whom God took away before them.
\v 26 And the God of Israel raised up the spirit of Phul king of the Assyrians, and the spirit of Thelgathphalnasar king of Assur: and he transported Ruben, and Gad, and the half tribe of Manasses, and brought them into Lahela, and into Habor, and to Ara, and to the river of Gozan, until this day.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 The sons of Levi: Gerson, Caath, and Merari.
\v 2 The sons of Caath: Amram, Isaar, Hebron, and Oziel.
\v 3 The children of Amram: Aaron, Moyses, and Maria. The sons of Aaron: Nadab and Abiu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\v 4 Eleazar begat Phinees, and Phinees begat Abisue, \f + \fr 6:4 \ft The lineal succession of High Priests from Aaron to the captivity in Babylon. Nicephorus counteth some others among these. li. 2. c. 4. Iosephus also differeth from this catalogue. li. 10. c. 11.\f*
\v 5 and Abisue begat Bocci, and Bocci begat Ozi.
\v 6 Ozi begat Zaraias, and Zaraias begat Maraioth.
\v 7 Moreover Meraioth begat Amarias, and Amarias begat Achitob.
\v 8 Achitob begat Sadoc, and Sadoc begat Achimaas,
\v 9 Achimaas begat Azarias, Azarias begat Johanan,
\v 10 Johanan begat Azarias. The same is he that executed the priestly office in the house, which Salomon built in Jerusalem.
\v 11 And Azarias begat Amarias, and Amarias begat Achitob, \x + \xo 6:11 \xt 2. Paral. 26.\x*
\v 12 and Achitob begat Sadoc, and Sadoc begat Sellum,
\v 13 Sellum begat Helcias, and Helcias begat Azarias,
\v 14 Azarias begat Saraias, & Saraias begat Josedec.
\v 15 Moreover Josedec went forth, when our Lord transported Juda and Jerusalem by the hands of Nabuchodonosor.
\v 16 The sons then of Levi: Gerson, Caath, and Merari.
\v 17 And these be the names of the sons of Gerson: Lobni and Semei.
\v 18 The sons of Caath: Amram, and Isaar, and Hebron, and Oziel.
\v 19 The sons of Merari: Moholi and Musi. And these are the kindreds of Levi according to their families.
\v 20 Gerson, Lobni his son, Jahath his son, Zamma his son,
\v 21 Joah his son, Addo his son, Zara his son, Jethrai his son.
\v 22 The sons of Caath, Aminadab his son, Core his son, Asir his son,
\v 23 Elcana his son, Abiasaph his son, Asir his son.
\v 24 Thahath his son, Uriel his son, Ozias his son, Saul his son.
\v 25 The sons of Elcana: Amasai, and Achimoth,
\v 26 & Elcana: The sons of Elcana: Sophai his son, Nahath his son,
\v 27 Eliab his son, Jeroham his son, Elcana his son.
\v 28 The sons of Samuel: the first-begotten Vasseni, and Abia.
\v 29 And the sons of Merari, Moholi: Lobni his son, Semei his son, Oza his son,
\v 30 Sammaa his son, Haggia his son, Asaia his son.
\v 31 These are they, whom David appointed over the singing men of the house of our Lord, since the Ark was placed:
\v 32 & they ministered before the tabernacle of testimony, singing, until Salomon built the house of our Lord in Jerusalem: & they stood according to their order in the ministry.
\v 33 And these are they, which assisted with their sons, of the sons of Caath, Hemam singing man, the son of Joel, the son of Samuel,
\v 34 the son of Elcana, the son of Jeroham, the son of Eliel, the son of Thohu,
\v 35 the son of Suph, the son of Elcana, the son of Mahath, the son of Amasai,
\v 36 the son of Elcana, the son of Johel, the son of Azaria, the son of Sophonias,
\v 37 the son of Thahath, the son of Asir, the son of Abiasaph, the son of Core,
\v 38 the son of Isaar, the son of Caath, the son of Levi, the son of Israel.
\v 39 And his brother Asaph, who stood on his right hand, Asaph the son of Barachias, the son of Samaa,
\v 40 the son of Michael, the son of Basaia, the son of Melchia.
\v 41 the son of Athanai, the son of Zara, the son of Adaia,
\v 42 the son of Ethan, the son of Zamma, the son of Semei.
\v 43 the son of Jeth, the son of Gerson, the son of Levi.
\v 44 And the children of Merari their brethren, on the left hand, Ethan the son of Cusi, the son of Abdi, the son of Maloch,
\v 45 the son of Hasabia, the son of Amasia, the son of Helcias,
\v 46 the son of Amasai, the son of Boni, the son of Somer,
\v 47 the son of Moholi, the son of Musi, the son of Merari, the son of Levi.
\v 48 Their brethren also the Levites, which were ordained for all the ministry of the tabernacle of the house of our Lord.
\v 49 But Aaron, and his sons burnt incense upon the altar of holocaust, and upon the altar of incense, for every work of Sancta Sanctorum: and to pray for Israel according to all things, which Moyses the servant of God commanded.
\v 50 And these are the sons of Aaron: Eleazar his son, Phinees his son, Abisue his son.
\v 51 Bocci his son, Ozi his son, Zarahia his son,
\v 52 Meraioth his son, Amarias his son, Achitob his son,
\v 53 Sadoc his son, Achimaas his son. \f + \fr 6:53 \ft In Sadoc. (3. Reg. 2.) the high Priesthood was reduced to the line of Eleazar which by God's ordinance was translated to Heli of Ithamar's line: but still continued in the line of Aaron. The rest of Sadoch's line by Achimaas &c. to Josedech in the captivity appeareth before, v. 9. ad 15.\f*
\v 54 And these are their habitations by the towns and confines, to wit, of the sons of Aaron, according to the kindreds of the Caathites: for they were fallen to them by lot.
\v 55 They gave therefore to them Hebron in the Land of Juda, and the suburbs thereof round about:
\v 56 but the fields of the city, and the towns to Caleb the son of Jephone.
\v 57 Moreover to the sons of Aaron they gave cities, to fly unto, Hebron, and Lobna, and the suburbs thereof,
\v 58 Jether also and Esthemo with the suburbs thereof, yea and Helon, and Dabir with their suburbs:
\v 59 Asan also and Bethsemes, & their suburbs.
\v 60 And of the tribe of Benjamin: Gabee and the suburbs thereof, Almath with the suburbs thereof, Anothoth also with the suburbs thereof. All the cities, thirteen, by their kindreds.
\v 61 And to the children of Caath the residue of their kindred they gave of the half tribe of Manasses in possession ten cities.
\v 62 Moreover to the children of Gerson by their kindreds of the tribe of Issachar, and of the tribe of Aser, and of the tribe of Nephthali, and of the tribe of Manasses in Basan, thirteen cities.
\v 63 And to the sons of Merari by their kindreds of the tribe of Ruben, and of the tribe of Gad, & of the tribe of Zabulon, they gave by lot twelve cities.
\v 64 Also the children of Israel gave to the Levites cities, and their suburbs:
\v 65 and they gave by lot, of the tribe of the children of Juda, and of the tribe of the children of Simeon, & of the tribe of the children of Benjamin, these cities, which they called by their names,
\v 66 and to them, that were of the kindred of the sons of Caath, & the cities in their borders were of the tribe of Ephraim.
\v 67 They therefore gave them cities, to fly unto, Sichem with the suburbs thereof in mount Ephraim, and Gazer with the suburbs thereof,
\v 68 Jecmaan also with the suburbs thereof, & Bethhoron in like manner,
\v 69 moreover Helon also with the suburbs thereof, and Gethremmon in like manner.
\v 70 Moreover of the half tribe of Manasses Aner & the suburbs thereof, Balaam & the suburbs thereof: to wit, to them, which were left of the kindred of the sons of Caath.
\v 71 And to the sons of Gerson of the kindred of the half tribe of Manasses, Gaulon in Basan, & the suburbs thereof, & Astaroth with the suburbs thereof.
\v 72 Of the tribe of Issachar, Cedes & the suburbs thereof, & Dabereth with the suburbs thereof,
\v 73 Ramoth also & the suburbs thereof, & Anem with the suburbs thereof.
\v 74 And of the tribe of Aser: Masal with the suburbs thereof, and Abdon in like manner,
\v 75 Hucac also and the suburbs thereof, & Rohob with the suburbs thereof.
\v 76 Moreover of the tribe of Nephthali, Cedes in Galilee and the suburbs thereof, Hamon with the suburbs thereof, and Cariathaim, and the suburbs thereof.
\v 77 And to the rest of the sons of Merari: of the tribe of Zabulon Remmono and the suburbs thereof, and Thabor with the suburbs thereof:
\v 78 beyond Jordan also over against Jericho, against the East of Jordan, of the tribe of Ruben, Bosor in the wilderness with the suburbs thereof, and Jassa with the suburbs thereof,
\v 79 Cademoth also and the suburbs thereof, and Mephaath with the suburbs thereof.
\v 80 Moreover also of the tribe of Gad, Ramoth in Galaad and the suburbs thereof, and Manaim with the suburbs thereof,
\v 81 Yea and Hesebon with the suburbs thereof, and Jezer with the suburbs thereof.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 Moreover the sons of Issachar: Thola, and Phua, Jasub & Simeron, four,
\v 2 The sons of Thola: Ozi and Raphaia, and Jeriel, and Jemai, and Jebsem, and Samuel. Princes by the houses of their kindreds. Of the stock of Thola were numbered most valiant men in the days of David, two and twenty thousand six hundred.
\v 3 The sons of Ozi: Izrahia, of whom were born Michael, and Obadia, and Joel, and Jesia, five, all Princes.
\v 4 And with them by their families and peoples, ready girded to battle, most valiant men, six and thirty thousand: for they had many wives, and children.
\v 5 Their brethren also through all the kindred of Issachar, most strong to fight, were numbered four score and seven thousand.
\v 6 The sons of Benjamin: Bela, and Bechor, and Jadihel, three. \f + \fr 7:6 \ft Gen. 46. this third son is called Asbel: & seven more are there recited. And so in the rest is much difference: but all may be reconciled by such rules as are noted. chap. 1.\f*
\v 7 The sons of Bela: Esbon, and Ozi, and Oziel, and Jerimoth, and Urai, five Princes of their families, and most strong to fight, and their number was twenty two thousand and thirty four.
\v 8 Moreover the sons of Bechor: Zamira, and Joas, and Eliezer, and Elioenai, and Amri, and Jerimoth, and Abia, and Anathoth, and Almath. All these the sons of Bechor.
\v 9 And there were numbered by their families Princes of their kindreds most valiant unto battle, twenty thousand and two hundred.
\v 10 Moreover the sons of Jadihel: Balan. And the sons of Balan: Jehus, and Benjamin, and Aod, and Chanana, and Zethan, and Tharsis, Ahisahar.
\v 11 All these the sons of Jadihel, Princes of their kindreds, most valiant men, seventeen thousand, & two hundred going forth to battle.
\v 12 Sepham also, & Hapham, the sons of Hir: and Hasim the sons of Aher.
\v 13 And the sons of Nephthali: Jasiel, and Guni, and Jezer, and Sellum, the sons of Bala.
\v 14 Moreover the son of Manasses, Ezriel: & his concubine the Syrian bare Machir the father of Galaad.
\v 15 And Machir took wives for his sons Happhim, & Saphan: & he had a sister named Maacha: the name of the second Salphaad, and to Salphaad were born daughters.
\v 16 And Maacha the wife of Machir bare a son, and she called his name Phares: moreover the name of his brother, was Sares: and his sons, Ulam and Recen.
\v 17 And the son of Ulam, Badan. These are the children of Galaad, the son of Machir, the son of Manasses.
\v 18 And his sister Queen bare Goodlieman, & Abiezer, & Mohola. \f + \fr 7:18 \ft Molecheth, Regina; Queen.\f* \f + \fr 7:18 \ft Ishod, Virum decorum, that is, A comely, personable, or goodly man. So we leave the Hebrew names in this place because S. Jerom, and the whole Church doth so in the Latin text, which we translate.\f*
\v 19 And the sons of Semida were, Ahin, & Sechem, and Leci, & Anian.
\v 20 And the sons of Ephraim: Suthala, Bared his son, Thahath his son, Elada his son, Thahath his son, and this man's son Zabad,
\v 21 and this man's son Suthala, and this man's son Ezer, and Elad: and the men of Geth born in the land slew them, because they came down to invade their possessions.
\v 22 Ephraim therefore their father mourned many days, and his brethren came to comfort him.
\v 23 And he went in unto his wife: who conceived and bare a son, and he called his name Beria, for that he was born in the evils of his house:
\v 24 and his daughter was Sara, who built Bethhoron, the nether and the upper, and Ozensara.
\v 25 Moreover his son Rapha, and Reseph, and Thale, of whom was born Thaan,
\v 26 who begat Laadan: this man's son also was Ammiud, who begat Elisama,
\v 27 of whom was born Nun, who had Josue his son.
\v 28 And their possession and habitation was Bethel with her daughters, and against the east of Noran, and on the west quarter of Gazer and her daughters, Sichem also with her daughters, as far as Asa with her daughters.
\v 29 Also near the children of Manasses Bethsan & her daughters, Thanach and her daughters, Mageddo and her daughters: Dor & her daughters. In these dwelt the children of Joseph, the son of Israel.
\v 30 The children of Aser: Jemna, and Jesua, and Jessui, and Baria, and Sara their sister.
\v 31 And the sons of Baria: Heber, & Melchiel: he is the father of Barsaith.
\v 32 And Heber begat Jephlat, & Somer, and Hotham, & Suaa their sister.
\v 33 The son of Jephlat: Phosech, & Chamaal, and Asoth: these be the sons of Jephlat.
\v 34 Moreover the sons of Somer: Ahi, and Roaga, and Haba, and Aram.
\v 35 and the sons of Helem his brother: Supha, and Jemna, and Selles, and Amal.
\v 36 The sons of Supha: Sue, Harnapher, and Sual, and Beri, and Jamra,
\v 37 Bosor, and Hod, & Samma, Salusa, & Jethran, & Bera.
\v 38 The sons of Jether: Jephone, and Phaspha, and Ara.
\v 39 And the sons of Olla: Aree, and Haniel and Resia.
\v 40 All these be the sons of Aser, Princes of their kindreds, the chosen and most valiant dukes of dukes: and their number of the age that was fit for battle, was six and twenty thousand.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 And Benjamin begat Bale his first begotten, Asbel the second, Ahara the third,
\v 2 Nohaa the fourth, and Rapha the fifth.
\v 3 And the sons of Bale were: Addar, and Gera, and Abiud,
\v 4 Abisue also, and Naaman, and Ahoe,
\v 5 and also Gera, and Sephuphan, and Huram.
\v 6 These are the sons of Ahod, Princes of their kindreds that dwelt in Gabaa, which were transported into Manahath.
\v 7 And Naaman, and Achia, and Gera he transported them, and begat Oza, and Ahiud.
\v 8 Moreover he begat Saharaim in the country of Moab, after he dismissed Husim and Bara his wives.
\v 9 And of Hodes his wife he begat Jobab, and Sebia, and Mosa, and Molchom,
\v 10 Jehus also, and Sechia, and Marma. These are his sons Princes in their families.
\v 11 And Mehusim begat Abitob, and Elphaal.
\v 12 Moreover the sons of Elphaal Heber, and Misaam, and Samad: this man built Ono, and Lod, and her daughters.
\v 13 And Baria, and Sama Princes of their kindreds that dwelt in Aialon: these drove away the inhabitants of Geth.
\v 14 And Ahio, & Sesac, and Jerimoth,
\v 15 and Sabadia, and Arod, and Heder,
\v 16 Michael also, and Jespha, & Joha the sons of Baria.
\v 17 And Zabadia, and Mosollam, and Hezeci, and Heber,
\v 18 and Jesamari, and Jezlia, and Jobab sons of Elphaal,
\v 19 and Jacim, and Zechri, and Zabdi
\v 20 and Elioenai, and Selethai, and Eliel,
\v 21 and Adaia, and Baraia, and Samarath the sons of Semei.
\v 22 And Jespham, and Heber, and Eliel.
\v 23 and Abdon, and Zechri, and Hanan,
\v 24 and Hanania, and Ælam, and Anathothia,
\v 25 and Jephdaia, and Phanuel the sons of Sesac.
\v 26 and Samsari, and Sohoria and Otholia.
\v 27 and Jersia, and Elia, and Zechri, the sons of Jeroham.
\v 28 these be the Patriarchs, and Princes of their kindreds, which dwelt in Jerusalem.
\v 29 And in Gabaon dwelt Abigabaon, and the name of his wife Maacha:
\v 30 And his first-begotten son Abdon, and Sur, and Cis, and Baal, and Nadab.
\v 31 Gedor also, and Ahio, and Zacher, and Macelloth:
\v 32 and Macelloth begat Samaa: and they dwelt over against their brethren in Jerusalem with their brethren.
\v 33 And Ner begat Cis, and Cis begat Saul. Moreover Saul begat Jonathas, and Melchisua, and Abinadab, and Esbaal.
\v 34 And the son of Jonathas, Meribbaal: and Meribbaal begat Micha.
\v 35 The sons of Micha, Phithon, and Melech, and Tharaa, and Ahaz.
\v 36 And Ahaz begat Joada and Joada begat Alamath, and Azmoth, and Zamri: moreover Zamri begat Mosa,
\v 37 and Mosa begat Banaa, whose son was Rapha, of whom was born Elasa, who begat Asel.
\v 38 Moreover Asel had six sons of these names, Ezricam, Bochru, Ismahel, Saria, Obdia, and Hanan. All these the sons of Asel.
\v 39 And the sons of Esec his brother, Ulam the first-begotten, and Jehus the second, and Eliphalet the third.
\v 40 And the sons of Ulam were most strong men, and archers of great force: and having many sons and nephews, unto an hundred fifty. All these the children of Benjamin.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 All Israel therefore was numbered: and the sum of them was written in the Book of the kings of Israel & Juda and they were transported into Babylon for their sin. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft The genealogies of all Israel being hitherto recited before their captivity, others are now added which first returned to Jerusalem after their release.\f*
\v 2 And they that dwelt first in their possessions and in their cities: Israel, and the Priests, and the Levites, and the Nathineans.
\v 3 There dwelt in Jerusalem of the children of Juda, and of the children of Benjamin, also of the children of Ephraim, and Manasses.
\v 4 Othei the son of Ammiud, the son of Amri, the son of Omrai, the son of Bonni, of the sons of Phares the son of Juda.
\v 5 And of Siloni: Asaia the first-begotten, and his sons.
\v 6 And of the sons of Zara: Jehuel, and their brethren, six hundred ninety.
\v 7 Moreover of the sons of Benjamin: Salo the son of Mosollam, the son of Oduia the son of Asana:
\v 8 and Jobania the son of Jeroham: and Ela the son of Ozi the son of Mochori: and Mosollam the son of Saphatias, the son of Rahuel, the son of Jebania,
\v 9 and their brethren by their families, nine hundred fifty six. All these Princes of their kindreds by the houses of their fathers.
\v 10 And of the Priests: Jedaia, Joiarib, and Jachin:
\v 11 Azarias also the son of Helcias, the son of Mosollam, the son of Sadoc, the son of Maraioth, the son of Achitob, high Priest of the house of God.
\v 12 Moreover Adaias the son of Jeroham, the son of Phassur, the son of Melchias: and Maasai the son of Adiel, the son of Jezra, the son of Mosollam, the son of Mosollamith, the son of Emmer.
\v 13 their brethren also Princes by their families a thousand seven hundred three score, most able men of strength to the work of the ministry in the house of God.
\v 14 And of the Levites: Semeia the son of Hassub the son of Ezricam, the son of Hasebia of the sons of Merari.
\v 15 Bacbacar also a carpenter, and Galal, and Mathania the son of Micha, the son of Zechri the son of Asaph:
\v 16 and Obdia the son of Semei, the son of Galal, the son of Idithun: and Barachia the son of Asa, the son of Elcana, who dwelt in the courts of Netophati.
\v 17 And the porters: Sellum, and Accub, and Telmon, and Ahimam: and their brother Sellum the Prince,
\v 18 until that time, in the king's gate toward the east, waited by their courses of the children of Levi.
\v 19 But Sellum the son of Core the son of Abiasaph, the son of Core, with his brethren, and his father's house, these are the Corites over the works of the ministry, keepers of the entrances of the tabernacle: and their families in course keeping the entrance of the camp of our Lord.
\v 20 And Phinees the son of Eleasar, was their Prince before our Lord.
\v 21 Moreover Zacharias the son of Mosollamia, porter of the gate of the tabernacle of testimony.
\v 22 All these chosen men for porters, at every gate, two hundred twelve: and appointed out in their proper towns: Whom David and Samuel the seer appointed, upon their fidelity.
\v 23 as well them as their sons, in the doors of the house of our Lord, and in the tabernacle by their courses.
\v 24 By the four winds were the porters: that is to say, toward the East, and toward the West, & toward the North, & toward the South.
\v 25 And their brethren dwelt in villages, & came upon their Sabbaths from time to time.
\v 26 To these four Levites was committed all the number of porters, & they were over the chambers, and treasures of the house of our Lord.
\v 27 Also round about the temple of our Lord they abode in their watches: that when it was time, they in the morning might open the doors.
\v 28 Of these men's stock there were also over the vessels of the ministry: for by number the vessels were both brought in and carried out.
\v 29 Of them also they that had the implements of the sanctuary committed unto them, did oversee the flour, and wine, and oil, and frankincense, and spices.
\v 30 And the sons of Priests made ointments of the spices.
\v 31 And Mathathias a Levite the first-begotten of Sellum the Corite, was overseer of those things, which were fried in the frying pan.
\v 32 Moreover of the children of Caath their brethren, there were over the loaves of proposition, to prepare always new every Sabbath.
\v 33 These are the chief of the singing men by the families of the Levites, which abode in the chambers, that they might day and night continually serve in their ministry.
\v 34 The heads of the Levites, Princes in their families, tarried in Jerusalem.
\v 35 And in Gabaon abode Jehiel the father of Gabaon, and the name of his wife Maacha.
\v 36 His first-begotten son Abdon, and Sur, and Cis, and Baal, and Ner, and Nadab,
\v 37 Gedor also, and Ahio, and Zacharias, and Macelloth.
\v 38 Moreover Macelloth begat Samaan, these dwelt over against their brethren in Jerusalem, with their brethren.
\v 39 And Ner begat Cis: and Cis begat Saul: and Saul begat Jonathas, and Melchisua, and Abinadab, and Esbaal.
\v 40 And the son of Jonathas, Meribbaal: & Meribbaal begat Micha.
\v 41 Moreover the sons of Micha, Phithon, & Melech, & Tharaa, and Ahaz.
\v 42 And Ahaz begat Jara, & Jara begat Alamath, & Azmoth, & Zamri. And Zamri begat Mosa.
\v 43 And Mosa begat Banaa: whose son Raphaia begat Elasa: of whom was born Asel.
\v 44 Moreover Asel had six sons of these names, Ezricam, Bochru, Ismael, Saria, Obdia, Hanan, these are the sons of Asel.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 And the Philisthiims fought against Israel, and the men of Israel fled from the Palesthines, and they fell wounded in mount Gelboe. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft The second part. King Saul and all his family overthrown.\f*
\v 2 And when the Philisthians were come near pursuing Saul and his sons, they struck Jonathas, and Abinadab, and Melchisua the sons of Saul.
\v 3 And the battle grew sore against Saul, and the archers found him, and wounded him with arrows.
\v 4 And Saul said to his esquire: Draw thy sword, and kill me: lest perhaps these uncircumcised come, and deride me. But his harness-bearer would not, being frighted with fear: Saul therefore caught his sword, and fell upon it.
\v 5 Which when his harness-bearer had seen, to wit, that Saul was dead, himself also fell upon his sword, and died.
\v 6 Saul therefore died, and his three sons, and all his house fell together.
\v 7 Which when the men of Israel had seen that dwelt in the champion, they fled: and Saul and his sons being dead, they forsook their cities, and were dispersed hither and thither: and the Philisthiims came, and dwelt in them.
\v 8 The next day therefore the Philisthiims taking away the spoils of them that were slain, found Saul and his sons lying on mount Gelboe.
\v 9 And when they had spoiled him, and cut off his head, and stripped him of his armour, they sent into their land, that it should be carried about, & should be shewed in the temples of the idols, and to the people:
\v 10 & his armour they dedicated in the temple of their god, and the head they nailed up in the temple of Dagon.
\v 11 When the men of Jabes Galaad had heard this, to wit, all things that the Philisthiims had done upon Saul,
\v 12 every one of the valiant men arose, and took the bodies of Saul and of his sons, and brought them into Jabes, & buried their bones under an oak, that was in Jabes, and they fasted seven days.
\v 13 Saul therefore died for his iniquities, for that he transgressed the commandment of our Lord which he had commanded, and kept it not: yea and besides also consulted the Pythoness, \f + \fr 10:13 \ft He offered Sacrifice on an Altar without warrant. 1. Reg. 13. And destroyed not the Amalecites, as he was commanded. 1. Reg. 15.\f*
\v 14 and trusted not in our Lord: for the which he slew him, and transferred his Kingdom to David the son of Isai.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 All Israel therefore was gathered together to David in Hebron, saying: We are thy bone, and thy flesh. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft The third part. King David's reign and his special acts.\f*
\v 2 Yesterday also, and the day before, when Saul as yet reigned, thou wast he that didst lead out and lead in Israel: for to thee our Lord thy God said: Thou shalt feed my people Israel, and thou shalt be Prince over it.
\v 3 All the ancients therefore of Israel came to the king into Hebron, and David entered into a league with them before our Lord: and they anointed him king over Israel, according to the word of our Lord, which he spake in the hand of Samuel.
\v 4 David also went, and all Israel into Jerusalem. This is Jebus, where the Jebuseites were the inhabiters of the land.
\v 5 And they that dwelt in Jebus, said to David: Thou shalt not come in here. Moreover David took the tower of Sion, which is the City of David,
\v 6 & he said: Every one that shall among the first strike the Jebusite, shall be the Prince & chief captain. Joab therefore the son of Sarvia went up first, and was made the Prince.
\v 7 And David dwelt in the tower, and therefore it was called the City of David.
\v 8 And he built the City round about from Mello unto a round compass, and Joab built the rest of the city.
\v 9 And David prospered going and increasing, and the Lord of hosts was with him.
\v 10 These are the Princes of the valiant men of David, which holp him to be made king over all Israel according to the word of our Lord, which he spake to Israel
\v 11 And this is the number of David's strong ones: Jesbaam the son of Hachamoni Prince among thirty: this man lifted up his spear upon three hundred wounded at one time.
\v 12 And after him Eleazar his uncle's son an Ahohite, who was among the three mighties.
\v 13 This was with David in Phesdomim, when the Philisthiims were gathered to that place into battle: and the field of that country was full of barley, and the people was fled from the face of the Philisthiims.
\v 14 These stood in the midst of the field, and defended him: and when they had strucken the Philistheans, our Lord gave great health to his people.
\v 15 And there went down three of the thirty Princes to a rock, wherein David was, to the cave of Odollam, when the Philisthiims had camped in the Vale Raphaim.
\v 16 Moreover David was in a hold, and the ward of the Philisthimes in Bethlehem.
\v 17 David therefore desired and said: O that some man would give me water of the cistern of Bethlehem, which is in the gate.
\v 18 These three therefore went forward through the midst of the camp of the Philisthiims, and drew water of the cistern of Bethlehem, which was in the gate, & brought it to David to drink: who would not, but rather offered it to our Lord,
\v 19 saying: God forbid that in the sight of my God I should do this, and should drink the blood of these men: because in the peril of their lives they have brought me the water. And for this cause he would not drink. These things did the three most valiants.
\v 20 Abisai also the brother of Joab he was Prince of three, and he lifted up his spear against three hundred wounded, and he was among three most renowned,
\v 21 and among the second three he the noble one, and Prince of them: but yet unto the three first he raught not.
\v 22 Banaias the son of Joiada a most valiant man, of Cabseel: who had done many facts, he struck the two Ariel of Moab: & he went down, and slew the lion in the midst of the cistern in the time of snow. \f + \fr 11:22 \ft Two stout men of Moab, as if they had been lions. 2. Reg. 23. v. 20.\f*
\v 23 And he struck the Ægyptian, whose stature was of five cubits, and which had a spear as the weaver's beam: he therefore went down to him with a rod, and by force took away the spear that he held in his hand, and slew him with his own spear.
\v 24 These things did Banaias the son of Joiada, who was among the three valiants most renowned,
\v 25 the first among thirty, but yet the three he raught not: and David made him of his counsel.
\v 26 Moreover the most valiant men in the army, Asahel the brother of Joab, and Elchanan the son of his uncle of Bethlehem,
\v 27 Sammoth an Arorite, Helles a Phalonite,
\v 28 Ira the son of Acces a Thecaite, Abiezer an Anathothite,
\v 29 Sobbochai an Husathite, Ilai an Ahohite,
\v 30 Maharai a Netophathite, Heled the son of Baana a Netophathite.
\v 31 Ethai the son of Ribai of Gabaath the children of Benjamin, Banaia a Pharatonite,
\v 32 Hurai of the Torrent Gaas, Abiel an Arbathite, Azmoth a Bauramite, Eliaba a Salabonite.
\v 33 The sons of Assem a Gezonite, Jonathan the son of Sage an Ararite,
\v 34 Ahiam the son of Sachar an Ararite,
\v 35 Eliphal the son of Ur,
\v 36 Hepher a Mecherathite, Ahia Phelonite,
\v 37 Hesro a Carmelite, Naarai the son of Azbai,
\v 38 Joel the brother of Nathan, Mibahar the son of Agarai.
\v 39 Selec an Ammonite, Naharai a Berothite the armour-bearer of Joab the son of Sarvia,
\v 40 Ira a Jethreite, Gareb a Jethreite,
\v 41 Urias the Hetheite, Zabad the son of Oholi,
\v 42 Adina the son of Siza a Rubenite the Prince of the Rubenites, and with him thirty:
\v 43 Hanan the son of Maacha, and Josaphat a Mathanite,
\v 44 Ozia an Astarothite, Samma, and Jehiel the sons of Hotham an Arorite,
\v 45 Jedihel the son of Zamri, and Joha his brother a Thosaite,
\v 46 Eliel a Mahumite, and Jeribai, and Josaia the sons of Elnaim, and Jethma a Moabite, Eliel, and Obed, and Jasiel of Masobia.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 These also came to David into Siceleg, when as yet he fled from Saul the son of Cis, the which were most valiant and excellent warriors,
\v 2 drawing the bow, & hurling with both hands stones in slings, & shooting arrows directly: of the brethren of Saul of Benjamin.
\v 3 The Prince Ahiezer, and Joas the sons of Samaa a Gabaathite, and Jaziel, and Phallet the sons of Azmoth, and Beracha, and Jehu an Anothothite.
\v 4 Samaias also a Gabaonite the most valiant amongst the thirty and above the thirty. Jeremias, and Jeheziel, and Johanan, & Jezabad a Gaderothite.
\v 5 And Eluzai, and Jerimuth, and Baalia, & Samaria, and Saphatia an Haruphite.
\v 6 Elcana, and Jesia, and Azareel, and Joezer, and Jesbaam of Carehim:
\v 7 Joela also, and Zabadia the sons of Jeroham of Gedor.
\v 8 Yea and of Gaddi also there fled to David, when he lay hid in the desert most valiant men, & the best warriors, holding shield and spear: their faces as the faces of a lion, & swift as the roe-bucks on the mountains:
\v 9 Ezer the Prince, Obdias the second, Eliab the third,
\v 10 Masmana the fourth, Jeremias the fifth,
\v 11 Ethi the sixth, Eliel the seventh,
\v 12 Johanan the eight, Elzebad the ninth,
\v 13 Jeremias the tenth, Machbanai the eleventh,
\v 14 these of the children of Gad were the Princes of his army. The meanest was captain over an hundred soldiers, & the greatest, over a thousand.
\v 15 These are they which passed Jordan the first month, when it used to flow over his banks: & they chased away all that dwelt in the valleys toward the east quarter and the west.
\v 16 And there came also of Benjamin, & of Juda to the hold, wherein David abode.
\v 17 And David went out to meet them, & said: If you be come peaceably to me for to help me, my heart be joined to you, but if you lie in wait against me for my adversaries, whereas I have no iniquity in my hands, the God of our fathers see, and judge.
\v 18 But the spirit came on Amasai the Prince among thirty, & he said: We are thine, o David, & with thee, o son of Isai: peace, peace be to thee, and peace to thy helpers, for thy God helpeth thee. David therefore received them, and appointed them Princes of the band.
\v 19 Moreover of Manasses there fled to David, when he came with the Philisthiims against Saul to fight, and he fought not with them: because the Princes of the Philisthiims taking counsel sent him back, saying: with the peril of our head will he return to his lord Saul.
\v 20 Therefore when he returned into Siceleg, there fled to him of Manasses, Ednas, and Jozabab, and Jedihel, and Michael, and Ednas, & Jozabad, and Eliu, and Salathi, the Princes of a thousand in Manasses.
\v 21 These did aid David against the rovers: for they were all most valiant men, & were made commanders in the army.
\v 22 Yea & there came every day to David to help him, till it became a great number, as it were the army of God. \f + \fr 12:22 \ft An army of many good men, well disposed in order and concord, is called the army of God, like the great number of Angels, which to us are innumerable. Iob. 25.\f*
\v 23 This also is the number of the commanders of the army, which came to David, when he was in Hebron, to transfer the kingdom of Saul to him, according to the word of our Lord.
\v 24 The children of Juda bearing shield and spear, six thousand eight hundred well appointed to battle.
\v 25 Of the children of Simeon valiant men to fight, seven thousand one hundred.
\v 26 Of the children of Levi, four thousand six hundred.
\v 27 Joiada also Prince of the stock of Aaron, and with him three thousand seven hundred.
\v 28 Sadoc also a young man of goodly towardness, and the house of his father, Princes twenty two.
\v 29 And of the children of Benjamin the brethren of Saul, three thousand: for a great part of them as yet followed the house of Saul.
\v 30 Moreover of the children of Ephraim twenty thousand eight hundred valiant of strength, men renowned in their kindreds.
\v 31 And of the half tribe of Manasses, eighteen thousand, every one by their names, came to make David king.
\v 32 Also of the children of Issachar men of understanding, that knew all times to command what Israel should do, Princes two hundred: and all the rest of the tribe did follow their counsel.
\v 33 Moreover of Zabulon such as went forth to battle, and stood in array well appointed with armour of war, there came fifty thousand to aid, not in a double heart.
\v 34 And of Nephthali, commanders a thousand: & with them furnished with shield & spear, seven & thirty thousand.
\v 35 Of Dan also prepared to battle, twenty eight thousand six hundred.
\v 36 And of Aser going forth to fight, & provoking in battle, forty thousand.
\v 37 And beyond Jordan of the children of Ruben & of Gad, & the half part of the tribe of Manasses, furnished with armour of war, an hundred twenty thousand.
\v 38 All these men of war well appointed to fight, with perfect heart came into Hebron, to make David king over all Israel: yea & all the rest of Israel were of one heart, that David should be made king.
\v 39 And they were there with David three days eating and drinking: for their brethren had prepared for them.
\v 40 Yea and they that were near them as far as Issachar, and Zabulon, and Nephthali, brought loaves on Asses, and on camels, and on mules, and upon oxen, to eat: meal, figs, raisins, wine, oil, beeves, muttons, in all aboundance, for there was joy in Israel.
\c 13
\p
Obededom.
\v 1 And David took counsel with the tribunes, and centurions, and all the commanders,
\v 2 and he said to all the assembly of Israel: If it please you, & if the word which I speak proceed from our Lord God, let us send to the rest of our brethren into all the countries of Israel, & to the Priests, & Levites, that dwell in the suburbs of the cities, that they may be gathered together unto us,
\v 3 and we may bring again unto us the Ark of our God: for we sought it not in the days of Saul.
\v 4 And the whole multitude answered that it should be so done: for the word had pleased all the people.
\v 5 David therefore assembled all Israel from Sihor of Ægypt, till thou enter into Emath, to bring the Ark of God from Cariathiarim.
\v 6 And David went up, and every man of Israel to the hill of Cariathiarim which is in Juda, to fetch thence the Ark of our God sitting upon the Cherubim, where his name is invocated.
\v 7 And they laid the Ark of God upon a new wain, out of the house of Abinadab. And Oza and his brother did drive the wain.
\v 8 Moreover David, & all Israel played before our Lord with all their might in songs, and on harps, and psalteries, and timbrels, and cymbals, and trumpets.
\v 9 And when they were come to the Floor of Chidon, Oza stretched forth his hand, to hold up the Ark: for the oxe being wanton had made it lean a little a-side.
\v 10 Our Lord therefore was angry against Oza, & struck him, for that he had touched the Ark: and he died there before our Lord.
\v 11 And David was strucken sad, because our Lord had divided Oza: and he called that place, the Division of Oza until this present day.
\v 12 And he feared God at that time, saying: How may I bring in the Ark of God unto me?
\v 13 And for this cause he brought it not unto himself, that is, into the city of David, but turned it away into the house of Obededom the Getheite. \f + \fr 13:13 \ft Obededom was a Levite, (c. 15. v. 18.) and therefore more meet to keep the ark:\f* \f + \fr 13:13 \ft Called a Getheite because he had dwelt in the town of Geth.\f*
\v 14 Therefore the Ark of God remained in the house of Obededom three months: & our Lord blessed his house, and all things that he had.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 Hiram also the king of Tyre sent messengers to David, and cedar trees, and artificers for walls, and timber, to build him a house.
\v 2 And David knew that our Lord had established him to be king over Israel, and that his Kingdom was exalted over his people Israel.
\v 3 David also took other wives in Jerusalem: and he begat sons, and daughters.
\v 4 And these be their names, that were born to him in Jerusalem: Samua, and Sobab, Nathan, and Salomon.
\v 5 Jebahar, and Elisua, and Eliphalet,
\v 6 Noga also, and Napheg, and Japhia,
\v 7 Elisama, and Baalaida, and Eliphalet.
\v 8 And the Philisthiims hearing that David was anointed for king over all Israel, they went up all to seek him: which when David had heard, he went out to meet them.
\v 9 Moreover the Philisthiims coming, were spread abroad in the Vale Raphaim.
\v 10 And David consulted our Lord, saying: Shall I go up to the Philistians, and wilt thou deliver them into my hand? And our Lord said to him: Go up, and I will deliver them into thy hand.
\v 11 And when they were come up into Baalpharasim, David struck them there, and said: God hath divided mine enemies by my hand, as waters are divided: and therefore the name of that place was called Baal Pharasim.
\v 12 And they left there their gods, which David commanded to be burnt.
\v 13 And other time also the Philisthiims invaded, and were dispersed in the Vale.
\v 14 And David consulted God again, and God said to him: Go not up after them, retire from them, & thou shalt come against them over against the pear-trees.
\v 15 And when thou shalt hear the sound of one going in the top of the pear-trees, then shalt thou issue forth to battle. For God is gone forth before thee, to strike the camp of the Philisthiims.
\v 16 David therefore did as God had commanded him, & struck the camp of the Philisthians from Gabaon unto Gazera.
\v 17 And the name of David was bruited in all countries, and our Lord gave the dread of him over all nations.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 He made also houses for himself in the city of David: and built a place for the Ark of God, and pitcht a tabernacle for it.
\v 2 Then said David: It is unlawful that the Ark of God be carried of any man, but of the Levites: whom our Lord chose to carry it, and to minister unto himself for ever.
\v 3 And he gathered together all Israel into Jerusalem, that the Ark of God might be brought into his place, which he had prepared for it.
\v 4 Moreover also the sons of Aaron, and the Levites.
\v 5 Of the children of Caath, Uriel was the Prince, and his brethren an hundred twenty.
\v 6 Of the sons of Merari, Asaia the Prince: and his brethren two hundred twenty.
\v 7 Of the sons of Gersom, Joel the Prince: and his brethren an hundred thirty.
\v 8 Of the sons of Elisaphan, Semeias the Prince: and his brethren two hundred.
\v 9 Of the sons of Hebron, Eliel the Prince: and his brethren eighty.
\v 10 Of the sons of Oziel, Aminadab the Prince: and his brethren an hundred twelve.
\v 11 And David called Sadoc and Abiathar the Priests, and the Levites, Uriel, Asaia, Joel, Semeia, Eliel, and Aminadab:
\v 12 and he said to them: You that are the Princes of the Levitical families, be sanctified with your brethren, and fetch the Ark of our Lord the God of Israel to the place, which is prepared for it:
\v 13 lest as from the beginning, because you were not present, our Lord struck us: so now also it come to pass, we doing some unlawful thing.
\v 14 The Priests therefore, and the Levites were sanctified, to carry the Ark of our Lord the God of Israel.
\v 15 And the sons of Levi took the Ark of God, as Moyses had commanded, according to the word of our Lord, upon their shoulders, on bars.
\v 16 And David said to the Princes of the Levites, that they should appoint of their brethren singing men on musical instruments, to wit, on nables, and harps, and cymbals, that the sound of joy might resound on high.
\v 17 And they appointed Levites: Heman the son of Joel, and of his brethren Asaph the son of Barachias: and of the children of Merari, their brethren: Ethan the son of Casaia.
\v 18 And with them their brethren: in the second order, Zacharias, & Ben, & Jaziel, and Semiramoth, and Jahiel, and Ani, Eliab, and Banaias, and Maasias, and Mathathias, and Eliphalu, and Macenias, and Obededom, and Jehiel, porters.
\v 19 Moreover them that sang, Heman, Asaph and Ethan: sounding on brazen cymbals.
\v 20 And Zacharias, and Oziel, and Semiramoth, and Jahiel, and Ani, and Eliab, and Maasias, and Banaias upon nables sang mysteries.
\v 21 Moreover Mathathias, and Eliphalu, and Macenias, and Obededom, and Jehiel, and Ozaziu, upon harps for the octave sang a triumphant song.
\v 22 And Chonenias the Prince of the Levites, was chief over Prophecy, to begin the melody: for he was very cunning.
\v 23 And Barachias, and Elcana: door keepers of the Ark.
\v 24 Moreover Sebenias, and Josaphat, and Nathanael, and Amasai, and Zacharias, and Banaias, and Eliezer Priests, sounded with trumpets, before the Ark of God: and Obededom, and Jehias kept the door of the Ark.
\v 25 Therefore David and all the ancients of Israel, and the tribunes, went to fetch the Ark of the covenant of our Lord, out of the house of Obededom with joy.
\v 26 And when God had holpen the Levites, which carried the Ark of the covenant of our Lord, there were immolated seven oxen, and seven rams.
\v 27 Moreover David was clothed with a robe of fine linen, & all the Levites that carried the Ark, and the singing men, and Chonenias the Prince of prophecy among the singers: and David also was clothed with an Ephod of linen. \f + \fr 15:27 \ft Another linen garment used by Prophets, such as Samuel did wear being a child. 1. Reg. 2.\f*
\v 28 And all Israel brought the Ark of the covenant of our Lord in jubilee, and sounding with the sound of shalm, and with trumpets, and cymbals, and nables, and harps.
\v 29 And when the Ark of the covenant of our Lord was come unto the city of David, Michol the daughter of Saul looking forth through a window, saw David the king dancing and playing, and she despised him in her heart.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 They therefore brought the Ark of God, and set it in the midst of the tabernacle, which David had pitched for it: and they offered holocausts, and pacifics before God.
\v 2 And when David had finished offering holocausts, and pacifics, he blessed the people in the name of our Lord. \f + \fr 16:2 \ft Not only King David being a holy Prophet, but any other Superior might bless his subjects.\f*
\v 3 And he divided to all throughout every one, from man unto woman, a loaf of bread, and a piece of roasted beef, and flour fried with oil.
\v 4 And he appointed before the Ark of our Lord of the Levites, that should minister, and should remember his works, and glorify, and praise our Lord the God of Israel: \f + \fr 16:4 \ft That he also disposed certain offices to Levites was by special privilege, which was no prejudice to the high Priest's authority, for superior power is proved by God's institution, rather than by facts, either of good men, which do many things by way of dispensation, or of evil usurping without warrant, that to them pertaineth not. For it is clear that God instituted supreme spiritual power in the high Priest, Deut. 17. And all kings and temporal princes are to receive the law at the Priest's hand, ibidem. v. 18. Eleazar the high Priest was appointed to consult our Lord for Iosue, Nu. 18. Finally by God's ordinance, the law of truth was in the mouth of Priests. Malac. 2.\f*
\v 5 Asaph the Prince, and the second after him Zacharias: moreover Jahiel, and Semiramoth, and Jehiel, and Mathathias, and Eliab, and Banaias, and Obededom: and Jehiel over the instruments of psaltery, and the harps: and Asaph to sound upon the cymbals:
\v 6 but Banaias, and Jaziel Priests, to sound the trumpet continually before the Ark of the covenant of our Lord.
\v 7 In that day David made Asaph, prince to confess to our Lord and his brethren.
\v 8 Confess ye to our Lord, and invocate his name: make his inventions known among the peoples. \x + \xo 16:8 \xt Psal. 104.\x*
\v 9 Chant to him, and sing to him: & tell ye all his marvelous things.
\v 10 Praise ye his holy name: let the heart of them rejoice, that seek our Lord.
\v 11 Seek ye our Lord, and his power: seek ye his face always.
\v 12 Remember his marvelous things which he hath done: his signs, and the judgements of his mouth.
\v 13 The seed of Israel his servant: the children of Jacob his elect.
\v 14 He is the Lord our God: in all the earth are his judgements.
\v 15 Remember for ever his covenant: the word, which he commanded unto a thousand generations.
\v 16 Which he covenanted with Abraham: and his oath with Isaac.
\v 17 And he appointed it to Jacob for a precept: and to Israel for an everlasting covenant:
\v 18 Saying: To thee will I give the Land of Chanaan: the cord of your inheritance.
\v 19 When they were few in number: small and sojourners thereof.
\v 20 And they passed from nation into nation: and from Kingdom to another people.
\v 21 He suffered not any man to calumniate them: but rebuked kings for their sake.
\v 22 Touch not my anointed: and unto my Prophets be not malicious.
\v 23 Sing ye to our Lord all the earth: shew forth from day to day his salvation. \x + \xo 16:23 \xt Psa. 95.\x*
\v 24 Tell his glory among the gentiles: among all peoples his marvelous works.
\v 25 Because our Lord is great, and laudable exceedingly: and terrible over all gods.
\v 26 For all the gods of the peoples, be idols: but our Lord made the heavens.
\v 27 Confession and magnificence before him: strength and joy in his place.
\v 28 Bring to our Lord ye families of peoples: bring to our Lord glory and empire.
\v 29 Give our Lord glory, to his name, elevate sacrifice, and come ye in his sight: and adore our Lord in holy honour.
\v 30 Let all the earth be moved before his face: for he founded the world unmovable.
\v 31 Let the heavens be glad, and the earth rejoice: and let them say among nations, Our Lord hath reigned.
\v 32 Let the sea thunder, and the fullness thereof: let the fields rejoice, and all things that are in them.
\v 33 Then shall the trees of the forest praise before our Lord: because he is come to judge the earth.
\v 34 Confess ye to our Lord, because he is good: because his mercy is for ever. \x + \xo 16:34 \xt Psa. 105.\x*
\v 35 And say ye: Save us o God our Saviour: and gather us together, and deliver us out of the nations, that we may confess to thy holy name, and may rejoice in thy songs.
\v 36 Blessed be our Lord the God of Israel from eternity unto eternity: and let all the people say: Amen, and hymn to God.
\v 37 He therefore left Asaph there before the Ark of the covenant of our Lord, and his brethren to minister in the presence of the Ark continually day by day, & in their courses.
\v 38 Moreover Obededom, and his brethren sixty eight: and Obededom the son of Idithun, and Hosa he appointed for porters.
\v 39 And Sadoc the Priest, and his brethren Priests, before the tabernacle of our Lord in the excelse, which was in Gabaon,
\v 40 that they should offer holocausts to our Lord upon the altar of holocaust continually, morning and evening, according to all things that are written in the law of our Lord, which he commanded Israel.
\v 41 And after him Heman, and Idithun, and the rest of the chosen men, every one by his name to confess unto our Lord: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 42 Heman also and Idithun sounding the trumpet, and quavering on the cymbals, and all musical instruments to sing unto God: and the sons of Idithun he made porters.
\v 43 And all the people returned into their house: and David, to bless also his house.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 And when David dwelt in his house, he said to Nathan the Prophet: Behold I dwell in a house of cedar: and the Ark of the covenant of our Lord is under skins.
\v 2 And Nathan said to David: All things, that are in thy heart do: for God is with thee.
\v 3 Therefore that night the word of God came to Nathan, saying:
\v 4 Go, and speak to David my servant: Thus saith our Lord: Thou shalt not build me a house to dwell in.
\v 5 For neither have I remained in house from the time, that I brought out Israel, until this day: but I have been always changing places of tabernacle, & in tent,
\v 6 abiding with all Israel. Did I speak to one, at the least, of all the judges of Israel whom I commanded to feed my people, and did I say: Why have you not built me a house of cedar?
\v 7 Now therefore so shalt thou speak to my servant David: Thus saith the Lord of hosts: I took thee, when in the pastures thou didest follow the flock, that thou shouldest be Prince of my people Israel.
\v 8 And I have been with thee whither soever thou wentest: and I have slain all thine enemies before thee, and have made thee a name as of one of the great ones, that are renowned in the earth.
\v 9 And I have given a place to my people Israel: it shall be planted, and shall dwell therein, and shall be moved no more, neither shall the children of iniquity consume them, as from the beginning,
\v 10 since the days that I gave judges to my people Israel, & humbled all thine enemies. I therefore tell thee, that our Lord will build thee a house. \f + \fr 17:10 \ft That is continue and preserve thy seed, & family, as we see it performed even to the B. Virgin Mary and Christ of the house of David. Mat. 1. Luc. 2. 3.\f*
\v 11 And when thou shalt have accomplished thy days to go to thy fathers, I will raise up thy seed after thee, which shall be of thy children: and I will establish his Kingdom.
\v 12 He shall build me a house, and I will confirm his throne for ever.
\v 13 I will be to him for a father, and he shall be to me for a son: and my mercy I will not take from him, as I took from him, that was before thee.
\v 14 And I will establish him in my house, and in my Kingdom for ever: and his throne shall be most firm for ever.
\v 15 According to all these words, and according to all this vision, so spake Nathan to David.
\v 16 And when king David came, and sat before our Lord, he said: Who am I Lord God, and what is my house, that thou shouldest give me such things?
\v 17 But this also hath seemed little in thy sight, and therefore thou hast spoken concerning the house of thy servant for time to come also: and hast made me renowned above all men Lord God.
\v 18 What can David add farther, whereas thou hast so glorified thy servant, and known him?
\v 19 Lord for thy servant according to thy heart thou hast done all this magnificence, and would have all thy great wonders to be known.
\v 20 Lord, there is not the like to thee: and there is none other beside thee, of all whom we have heard with our ears.
\v 21 For what other is there, as thy people Israel, one nation in the earth, to the which God went, to deliver it and make it his people, and with his greatness & terrors cast out the nations before the face of it, which he delivered out of Ægypt?
\v 22 And thou hast made thy people Israel to be thy people for ever, and thou Lord art made the God thereof.
\v 23 Now therefore Lord, the word, which thou hast spoken to thy servant, and concerning his house, be it confirmed for ever, and do as thou hast spoken.
\v 24 And let thy name remain and be magnified for ever: and let it be said: The Lord of hosts is God of Israel, & the house of David his servant permanent before him.
\v 25 For thou Lord my God hast revealed the ear of thy servant, to build him a house: and therefore thy servant hath found confidence, to pray before thee.
\v 26 Now therefore Lord thou art God: & thou hast spoken to thy servant so great benefits.
\v 27 And thou hast begun to bless the house of thy servant, that it be always before thee: for thee o Lord blessing it, it shall be blessed for ever.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass after these things, that David struck the Philisthiims, and humbled them, and took away Geth, and her daughters out of the hand of the Philisthiims, \f + \fr 18:1 \ft The lesser towns and villages are commonly called the daughters of some great town or city to which they pertain.\f*
\v 2 and struck Moab; and the Moabites were made David's servants, offering him gifts.
\v 3 At that time David struck Adarezer also the king of Soba of the country of Hemath, when he went on to dilate his empire as far as the river Euphrates.
\v 4 David therefore took a thousand chariots of his, & seven thousand horsemen, & twenty thousand footmen, & he houghsinewed all the chariot horses, saving an hundred chariots, which he reserved to himself.
\v 5 And the Syrian also of Damascus came moreover, to give aid to Adarezer the king of Soba, but David struck also of his two & twenty thousand men.
\v 6 And he put soldiers in Damascus, that Syria also should serve him, & bring gifts. And our Lord holp him in all things, to the which he went.
\v 7 David also took the golden quivers, which the servants of Adarezer had, and he brought them into Jerusalem.
\v 8 Moreover of Thebath, and Chun, the cities of Adarezer, very much brass, of which Salomon made the brazen Sea, and Pillars, and brazen vessels.
\v 9 Which when Tou the king of Hemath had heard, to wit, that David had strucken all the army of Adarezer the king of Soba,
\v 10 he sent Adoram his son to king David, to desire peace of him, and to congratulate him that he had strucken, and had overthrown Adarezer: for Tou was adversary to Adarezer.
\v 11 But all the vessels also of gold, and silver, and brass king David consecrated to our Lord, with the silver and gold, which he had taken out of all the nations, as well of Idumea, and Moab, and the children of Ammon, as of the Philisthiims & Amalec. \f + \fr 18:11 \ft That which is dedicated to sacred use, is consecrated to God.\f*
\v 12 And Abisai the son of Sarvia struck Edom in the Vale of salt pits, eighteen thousand:
\v 13 and he appointed a garrison in Edom, that Idumea should serve David, and our Lord saved David in all things to which he went.
\v 14 David therefore reigned over all Israel, & did judgement and justice to all his people.
\v 15 Moreover Joab the son of Sarvia was over the army, and Josaphat the son of Ahilud commenter.
\v 16 And Sadoc the son of Achitob, and Ahimelech the son of Abiathar, Priests: and Susa, Scribe.
\v 17 Banaias also the son of Joiada over the legions Cerethi, and Phelethi: moreover the sons of David the chief at the king's hand.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 And it chanced that Naas the king of the children of Ammon died, and his son reigned for him. \x + \xo 19:1 \xt 2. Reg. 10.\x*
\v 2 And David said: I will do mercy with Hanon the son of Naas: for his father hath done me pleasure. And David sent messengers to comfort him upon the death of his father. Who when they were come into the land of the children of Ammon, to comfort Hanon,
\v 3 the Princes of the children of Ammon said to Hanon: Thou thinkest perhaps, that David for honour sake toward thy father hath sent some that should comfort thee; neither markest thou, that his servants are come to thee to espy, and seek out, and search thy land.
\v 4 Therefore Hanon made the servants of David bald, and shaved them, and cut away their coats from the buttocks to the feet, and sent them away.
\v 5 Who when they were gone, and had sent word to David, he sent to meet them (for they had sustained great reproach) and commanded them to tarry in Jericho, till their beard grew, and then they should return.
\v 6 And the children of Ammon seeing, that they had done injury to David, as well Hanon as the rest of the people, they sent a thousand talents of silver, to hire them chariots and horsemen out of Mesopotamia, and from Syria Maacha, and from Soba.
\v 7 And they hired two and thirty thousand chariots, & king Maacha with his people. Who when they were come, camped over against Medaba. The children of Ammon also being gathered together out of their cities, came to the battle.
\v 8 Which when David had heard, he sent Joab, and all the host of valiant men:
\v 9 and the children of Ammon issuing forth, put their army in array beside the gate of the city: and the kings, that were come to aid him, stood apart in the field.
\v 10 Joab therefore understanding that battle was made against him before and behind, chose the most valiant men of all Israel, and marched on against the Syrian.
\v 11 And the rest of the people he gave under the hand of Abisai his brother: and they went forth against the children of Ammon.
\v 12 And he said: If the Syrian shall overcome me, thou shalt aid me: and if the children of Ammon shall overcome thee, I will aid thee.
\v 13 Take courage, and let us play the men for our people, and for the cities of our God: and our Lord will do that which is good in his sight.
\v 14 Joab therefore marched on, and the people that were with him, against the Syrian to battle: and he put them to flight.
\v 15 Moreover the children of Ammon seeing that the Syrian was fled, themselves also fled from Abisai his brother, and went into the city: and Joab also returned into Jerusalem.
\v 16 But the Syrian seeing that he was fallen before Israel, sent messengers, and brought the Syrian, that was beyond the river: and Sophach the General of Adarezer's war, was their captain.
\v 17 Which when it was told David, he gathered together all Israel, and passed Jordan, and fell upon them, & directed his army against him, they fighting on the contrary part.
\v 18 And the Syrian fled from Israel: and David slew of the Syrians seven thousand chariots, and forty thousand footmen, and Sophach General of the army.
\v 19 And the servants of Adarezer seeing themselves to be overcome of Israel, fled to David, and served him: and Syria would no more give aid to the children of Ammon.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass after the compass of a year, at such time when kings are wont to go forth to battle, Joab gathered together the army and force of war, and spoiled the land of the children of Ammon: and went on and besieged Rabba. Moreover David tarried in Jerusalem, when Joab struck Rabba, and destroyed it. \x + \xo 20:1 \xt 2. Reg. 11.\x*
\v 2 And David took the crown of Melchom from his head, and found in it a talent weight of gold, and most precious pearls, and he made himself thereof a diadem: he took also the spoils of the city very much.
\v 3 And the people that was therein, he brought forth: and he made harrows, and sleds, and chariots shod with Iron to pass over them, so that they were cut asunder, and broken in pieces: so did David to all the cities of the children of Ammon: and he returned with all his people into Jerusalem.
\v 4 After these things there was war begun in Gazer against the Philisthians: in which Sobochai the Husathite struck Saphai of the kindred of Raphaim, and humbled them.
\v 5 Another battle also was fought against the Philisthians, wherein Adeodatus the son of Saltus a Bethlehemite struck the brother of Goliath the Getheite, the staff of whose spear was as it were a weaver's beam.
\v 6 But another battle also happened in Geth, wherein there was a very long man, having fingers and toes by six & six, that is, together four & twenty: who also was born of the stock of Rapha.
\v 7 This man blasphemed Israel: and Jonathan the son of Samaa the brother of David struck him. These be the children of Rapha in Geth, which fell by the hand of David and of his servants.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 But Satan rose against Israel: and moved David to number Israel.
\v 2 And David said to Joab, and to the Princes of the people: Go, and number Israel from Bersabee unto Dan, and bring me the number that I may know.
\v 3 And Joab, answered: Our Lord increase his people an hundred fold more than they are: are they not my lord king all thy servants? Why doth my lord seek this, which may be reputed for a sin to Israel?
\v 4 But the king's word prevailed more: and Joab went forth, and went about all Israel: and returned to Jerusalem.
\v 5 And he gave David the number of them, whom he had surveyed: and all the number of Israel was found a thousand thousand & an hundred thousand men that drew sword: and of Juda four hundred seventy thousand men of war.
\v 6 For Levi and Benjamin he numbered not: because Joab unwillingly executed the king's commandment.
\v 7 And that which was commanded displeased God: and he struck Israel.
\v 8 And David said to God: I have sinned exceedingly in that I would do this: I beseech thee take away the iniquity of thy servant, because I have done foolishly. \f + \fr 21:8 \ft King David was not without faith, nor hope, and yet was contaminate with iniquity, from which he prayed to be delivered.\f*
\v 9 And our Lord spake to Gad the Seer of David, saying:
\v 10 Go, & speak to David, & tell him: Thus saith our Lord: I give thee the choice of three things, choose one which thou wilt, & I will do it to thee.
\v 11 And when Gad was come to David, he said to him: Thus saith our Lord: Choose which thou wilt:
\v 12 either three years' famine: or three months to fly from thine enemies, and not to be able to escape their sword: or three days the sword of our Lord, and pestilence to be in the land, & the Angel of our Lord to kill in all the coasts of Israel: now therefore see what I shall answer him, that sent me.
\v 13 And David said to Gad: I am on every side in great distress: but it is better, that I fall into the hands of our Lord, because his mercies be many, than into the hands of men.
\v 14 Our Lord therefore sent the pestilence in Israel: and there fell of Israel seventy thousand men.
\v 15 He sent also an Angel into Jerusalem, to strike it: and when it was strucken, our Lord saw, and had compassion upon the greatness of the evil, and commanded the Angel, that smote: It is sufficient, now let thy hand cease. Moreover the Angel of our Lord stood beside the floor of Ornan the Jebusite.
\v 16 And David lifting up his eyes, saw the Angel of our Lord standing between heaven & earth, and a sword drawn in his hand, turned against Jerusalem: and they fell as well he as the ancients clothed in hair cloths, flat on the earth.
\v 17 And David said to God: Am not I he, that commanded the people to be numbered? It is I that have sinned: it is I that have done the evil: this flock what hath it deserved? Lord my God let thy hand be turned I beseech thee upon me, and upon my father's house: and let not thy people be strucken.
\v 18 And the Angel of our Lord commanded Gad to tell David, that he should go up, and build an altar to our Lord God in the floor of Ornan the Jebusite.
\v 19 David therefore went up according to the word of Gad, which he had spoken to him in the name of our Lord.
\v 20 Moreover Ornan when he had looked up, and seen the Angel, and his four sons with him, they hid themselves. For at that time he threshed wheat in the floor.
\v 21 Therefore when David came to Ornan, Ornan beheld him, and went forth to meet him out of the floor, and adored him flat on the ground.
\v 22 And David said to him: Give me the place of thy floor, that I may build therein an altar to our Lord: so that thou take as much silver as it is worth, and the plague may cease from the people.
\v 23 And Ornan said to David: Take it, and let my lord the king do whatsoever pleaseth him: yea the oxen also I give for holocaust, and the drays for wood, and wheat for sacrifice: I will give all things willingly. \f + \fr 21:23 \ft * little carts.\f*
\v 24 And king David said to him: It shall not be so, but I will give thee silver as much as it is worth: for I may not take it from thee, and so offer to our Lord holocausts given gratis.
\v 25 David therefore gave Ornan for the place, six hundred sicles of gold of most just weight.
\v 26 And he built there an altar to our Lord: and he offered holocausts, and pacifics, and he invocated our Lord, and he heard him in fire from heaven upon the altar of holocaust. \f + \fr 21:26 \ft God shewed by sending fire miraculously to burn the sacrifice, that he had heard David's prayer.\f*
\v 27 And our Lord commanded the Angel: & he turned his sword into the scabbard.
\v 28 David therefore forthwith seeing that our Lord had heard him in the floor of Ornan the Jebusite, immolated victims there.
\v 29 But the tabernacle of our Lord, which Moyses made in the desert, and the altar of holocausts, was at that time in the excelse of Gabaon.
\v 30 And David could not go to the altar to pray God there: for he had been frighted with exceeding fear, seeing the sword of the Angel of our Lord.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 And David said: This is the house of God, and this is an altar for holocaust to Israel.
\v 2 And he commanded that the proselytes of the land of Israel should be gathered together, and he appointed of them masons to hew stones and polish them, that the house of God might be built.
\v 3 David prepared also very much iron for the nails of the gates, and for the joinings and jointures: & of brass an innumerable weight.
\v 4 The cedar-trees also could not be esteemed, which the Sidonians and Tyrians brought down to David.
\v 5 And David said: Salomon my son is yet a little child and delicate, and the house which I would have to be builded to our Lord, must be such as may be renowned in all countries: I therefore will prepare him necessaries. And for this cause before his death he prepared all the expenses.
\v 6 And he called Salomon his son: and commanded him that he should build a house to our Lord the God of Israel.
\v 7 And David said to Salomon: My son, it was my will to have built a house to the name of our Lord my God.
\v 8 But the word of our Lord was made to me, saying: Thou hast shed much blood, and fought very many battles, thou canst not build a house to my name, so much blood being shed before me:
\v 9 the son, which shall be born to thee, shall be a most quiet man: for I will make him rest from all his enemies round about: and for this cause, he shall be called Peaceable: and I will give peace and quietness in Israel all his days. \f + \fr 22:9 \ft Salomon signifieth Peaceable, and therein, as in many other things, prefigured Christ, who amongst other names is called Prince of peace. Isai. 9.\f*
\v 10 He shall build a house to my name, and he shall be to me for a son, and I will be to him for a father: and I will establish the throne of his Kingdom over Israel for ever.
\v 11 Now therefore my son, Our Lord be with thee, and do thou prosper, and build the house of our Lord thy God, as he hath spoken of thee.
\v 12 Our Lord also give thee wisdom and understanding, that thou mayst be able to rule Israel, and to keep the law of our Lord thy God.
\v 13 For then thou shalt be able to prosper, if thou shalt keep the commandments, and judgments, which our Lord commanded Moyses to teach Israel: take courage and play the man, fear not, neither be dismayed.
\v 14 Behold I in my poverty have prepared the charges of the house of our Lord, of gold an hundred thousand talents, and of silver a thousand thousand talents, but of brass, & of iron there is no weight, for the number is surpassed with the greatness: timber & stones I have prepared to all the charges.
\v 15 Thou hast also very many artificers, hewers of stones, and masons, and carpenters, and of all occupations most skillful to make work
\v 16 in gold and silver and brass and iron, whereof there is no number. Rise therefore, and do it, and our Lord will be with thee.
\v 17 David also commanded all the Princes of Israel, that they should help Salomon his son.
\v 18 You see, quoth he, that our Lord your God is with you, and hath given you rest round about, and hath delivered all your enemies into your hands, and the land is subdued before our Lord, and before his people.
\v 19 Give therefore your heart and your souls, to seek our Lord your God: and arise, and build a sanctuary to our Lord God, that the Ark of the covenant of our Lord, and the vessels consecrated to our Lord, may be brought into the house, which is built to the name of our Lord.
\c 23
\p
\v 1 David therefore being old and full of days, made Salomon his son king over Israel
\v 2 And he gathered all the Princes of Israel, and the Priests and Levites.
\v 3 And the Levites were numbered from thirty years and upward: and there were found thirty eight thousand men.
\v 4 Of these were chosen, and distributed into the ministry of the house of our Lord four and twenty thousand: and of the overseers and judges, six thousand.
\v 5 Moreover four thousand porters: and as many singing to our Lord on instruments, which he had made to sing on.
\v 6 And David distributed them by the courses of the children of Levi, to wit, of Gerson, and Caath, and Merari. \f + \fr 23:6 \ft Aaron's sons being consecrated Priests according to God's ordinance, Levit. 8. & the Levites to do other offices about the tabernacle, Num. 3. & 4. King David (with Sadoc the high Priest, & other chief men. c. 24. v. 6. ) disposed them by lots which should serve by course, to sing & play on instruments, as well in the tabernacle now resting in Jerusalem, v. 26. as in the Temple when it should be built.\f*
\v 7 The sons of Gerson: Leedan, and Semei.
\v 8 The sons of Leedan: the Prince Jahiel, and Zethan, and Joel, three.
\v 9 The sons of Semei: Salomith, and Hosiel, and Aram, three: these be the Princes of the families of Leedan.
\v 10 Moreover the sons of Semei: Leheth, and Ziza, and Jaus, and Baria: these be the sons of Semei, four.
\v 11 And Leheth was the first, Ziza the second: moreover Jaus and Baria had not many children, and therefore they were counted in one family, and in one house.
\v 12 The children of Caath: Amram, and Isaar, Hebron, and Oziel, four.
\v 13 The sons of Amram, Aaron, and Moyses. And Aaron was separated to minister in Sancta Sanctorum, he and his sons for ever, and to burn incense to our Lord according to his rite, and to bless his name for ever.
\v 14 The sons of Moyses also the man of God were numbered in the tribe of Levi.
\v 15 The sons of Moyses: Gersom and Eliezer:
\v 16 the sons of Gersom: Subuel the first.
\v 17 And the sons of Eliezer were: Rohobia the first: and Eliezer had no more sons. Moreover the children of Rohobia were multiplied exceedingly.
\v 18 The sons of Isaar: Salomith the first.
\v 19 The sons of Hebron: Jeriau the first, Amarias the second, Jahaziel the third, Jecmaan the fourth.
\v 20 The sons of Oziel: Micha the first, Jesia the second.
\v 21 The sons of Merari: Moholi, and Musi. The sons of Moholi: Eleazar and Cis.
\v 22 And Eleazar died, and had no sons but daughters, and the sons of Cis their brethren took them.
\v 23 The sons of Musi: Moholi, and Eder, and Jerimoth, three.
\v 24 These be the children of Levi in their kindreds and families, Princes by courses, and number of every head, that did the works of ministry of the house of our Lord from twenty years, and upward.
\v 25 For David said: Our Lord the God of Israel hath given rest to his people, and the habitation of Jerusalem for ever.
\v 26 Neither shall it be the office of the Levites to carry any more the tabernacle, and all the vessels thereof to minister.
\v 27 According to the last precepts also of David the number of the children of Levi shall be numbered from twenty years & upward.
\v 28 And they shall be under the hand of the sons of Aaron for the service of the house of our Lord, in the entrances, and in the chambers, and in the place of purification, and in the Sanctuary, and in all the works of the ministry of the temple of our Lord.
\v 29 And the Priests over the loaves of proposition, and for the sacrifice of flour, and for cakes and azymes, and the frying pan and to roast, and over all weight and measure.
\v 30 But the Levites to stand in the morning to confess, and sing to our Lord: and in like manner at evening,
\v 31 as well in the oblation of the holocausts of our Lord, as in the Sabbaths and Calends, and the rest of the solemnities, according to the number, and ceremonies of every thing, continually before our Lord.
\v 32 And let them keep the observations of the tabernacle of covenant, and the rite of the Sanctuary, and the observance of the children of Aaron their brethren, that they minister in the house of our Lord.
\c 24
\p
according to their Priestly function, 20. likewise principal \add Levites in their offices.\add*
\v 1 Moreover to the sons of Aaron these were the partitions: The sons of Aaron: Nadab, and Abiu, and Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\v 2 But Nadab and Abiu died before their father without children: and Eleazar and Ithamar did the function of priesthood.
\v 3 And David divided them, that is, Sadoc of the sons of Eleazar, and Ahimelech of the sons of Ithamar, according to their courses and ministry.
\v 4 And there were found many more children of Eleazar among the principal men, than children of Ithamar. And he divided to them, that is, to the children of Eleazar, Princes by their families sixteen: and to the children of Ithamar by their families and houses eight.
\v 5 Moreover he divided both families between themselves by lots: for there were Princes of the Sanctuary, and Princes of God, as well of the children of Eleazar, as of the children of Ithamar. \f + \fr 24:5 \ft They were called Princes of the Sanctuary in respect of Sacrifices, & other sacred functions.\f* \f + \fr 24:5 \ft And Princes of God in regard of their spiritual jurisdiction in the Church, or house of God.\f*
\v 6 And Semeias wrote them, the son of Nathanael the Scribe a Levite, before the king and Princes, and Sadoc the Priest, and Ahimelech the son of Abiathar, the Princes also of the Priestly and Levitical families: one house, which was over the rest, Eleazar's, and another house, which had the rest under it, Ithamar's.
\v 7 And the first lot came forth to Joiarib, the second to Jedei,
\v 8 the third to Harim, the fourth to Seorim,
\v 9 the fifth to Melchia, the sixth to Maiman,
\v 10 the seventh to Accos, the eighth to Abia,
\v 11 the ninth to Jesua, the tenth to Sechenia,
\v 12 the eleventh to Eliasib, the twelfth to Jacim,
\v 13 the thirteenth to Hoppha, the fourteenth to Isbaab,
\v 14 the fifteenth to Belga, the sixteenth to Emmer,
\v 15 the seventeenth to Hezir, the eighteenth to Aphses,
\v 16 the nineteenth to Pheteia, the twentieth to Hezechiel,
\v 17 the one and twentieth to Jachin, the two and twentieth to Gamul,
\v 18 the three and twentieth to Dalaiau, the four and twentieth to Maaziau.
\v 19 These be their courses according to their ministries, to enter into the house of our Lord, and according to their rite under the hand of Aaron their father: as our Lord the God of Israel had commanded.
\v 20 Moreover of the children of Levi, which were remaining, there was Subael of the children of Amram: and of the children of Subael, Jehedeia.
\v 21 Also of the children of Rohobia the Prince of Jesias.
\v 22 And the son of Isaari Salemoth, & the son of Salemoth Jahath:
\v 23 and his son Jeriau the first, Amarias the second, Jahaziel the third, Jecmaan the fourth.
\v 24 The son of Oziel, Micha: the son of Micha, Samir.
\v 25 The brother of Micha, Jesia: and the son of Jesia, Zacharias.
\v 26 The sons of Merari: Moholi and Musi. The son of Oziau: Benno.
\v 27 The son also of Merari: Oziau, and Soam, and Zacchur, and Hebri.
\v 28 Moreover the son of Moholi: Eleazar, who had no children.
\v 29 And the son of Cis, Jeramael.
\v 30 The sons of Musi: Moholi, Eder, and Jerimoth. These be the sons of Levi according to the houses of their families.
\v 31 And they also did cast lots against their brethren the sons of Aaron before David the king, and Sadoc, and Ahimelech, and the Princes of the Priestly and Levitical families, as well the elder as the younger. Lot divided all equally.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 Therefore David, and the officers of the host separated for the ministry the sons of Asaph, and Heman, and Idithun: which should prophesy on harps, and psalteries, and cymbals, according to their number serving the office dedicated to them. \f + \fr 25:1 \ft Otherwise called Ethan, ch. 9. v. 44. c. 15.\f* \f + \fr 25:1 \ft They played on instruments, Psalms, and Canticles, made by Prophets.\f*
\v 2 Of the sons of Asaph: Zacchur, and Joseph, and Nathania, and Asarela, the sons of Asaph: under the hand of Asaph prophesying near the king.
\v 3 Moreover Idithun: the sons of Idithun, Godolias, Sori, Jeseias, and Hasabias, and Mathathias, six, under the hand of their father Idithun, who prophesied on harp over them that confessed and praised our Lord.
\v 4 Of Heman also: the sons of Heman Bocciau, Mathaniau, Oziel, Subuel, and Jerimoth, Hananias, Hanani, Eliatha, Geddelthi, and Romemthiezer, & Jesbacassa, Mellothi, Othir, Mahazioth:
\v 5 all these the sons of Heman the Seer of the king in the words of God, that he might exalt the horn: & God gave to Heman fourteen sons and three daughters.
\v 6 All under their fathers were distributed to sing in the temple of our Lord, on cymbals, & psalteries, and harps, for the ministries of the house of our Lord near the king: to wit, Asaph, and Idithun, and Heman.
\v 7 And the number of them with their brethren, that taught the song of our Lord, all the teachers two hundred eighty eight.
\v 8 And they did cast lots by their courses, equally as well the elder as the younger, the learned and the unlearned together.
\v 9 And the first lot came forth to Joseph, which was of Asaph. The second to Godolias, to him and his sons, and his brethren twelve.
\v 10 The third to Zachur, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 11 The fourth to Isari, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 12 The fifth to Nathanias, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 13 The sixth to Bocciau, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 14 The seventh to Isreela, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 15 The eighth to Jesaia, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 16 The ninth to Mathanias, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 17 The tenth to Semeias, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 18 The eleventh to Azareel, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 19 The twelfth to Hasabia, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 20 The thirteenth to Subael, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 21 The fourteenth to Mathathias, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 22 The fifteenth to Jerimoth, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 23 The sixteenth to Hananias, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 24 The seventeenth to Jesbacassa, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 25 The eighteenth to Hanani, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 26 The nineteenth to Mellothi, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 27 The twentieth to Eliatha, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 28 The one and twentieth to Othir, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 29 The two & twentieth to Geddelthi, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 30 The three and twentieth to Mahazioth, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\v 31 The four and twentieth to Romemthiezer, to his sons and his brethren twelve.
\c 26
\p
\v 1 And the divisions of the porters: of the Corites Meselemia, the son of Core, of the sons of Asaph.
\v 2 The sons of Meselemia: Zacharias the first-begotten, Jadihel the second, Zabadias the third, Jathanael the fourth,
\v 3 Ælam the fifth, Johanan the sixth, Elioenai the seventh.
\v 4 And the sons of Obededom Semeias the first-begotten, Jozabad the second, Joaha the third, Sachar the fourth, Nathanael the fifth,
\v 5 Ammiel the sixth, Issachar the seventh, Phollathi the eight: because our Lord blessed him.
\v 6 And to Semei his son were born sons, the chief of their families: for they were most valiant men.
\v 7 The sons then of Semeias: Othni, and Raphael, and Obed, Elizabad, and his brethren most valiant men: Eliu also, and Samachias.
\v 8 All these of the sons of Obededom: they, & their sons, & their brethren most able to minister, sixty two of Obededom.
\v 9 Moreover the sons of Meselemia, and their brethren most strong, eighteen.
\v 10 And of Hosa, that is, of the sons of Merari: Semri the Prince ( for he had not a first-begotten, and therefore his father made him chief) \f + \fr 26:10 \ft Either his first son was dead, or was not fit to be chief over the rest.\f*
\v 11 Helcias the second, Tabelias the third, Zacharias, the fourth: all these the sons, and brethren of Hosa, thirteen.
\v 12 These were divided into porters, that the Princes also of the watches, even as their brethren, might minister in the house of our Lord.
\v 13 Lots therefore were cast equally, both to little, and great, by their families, for every one of the gates.
\v 14 The lot then of the East fell to Selemia. Moreover to Zacharias his son, a most wise man, and skillful, the North quarter chanced by lot.
\v 15 But to Obededom and his sons, toward the South: in which part of the house was the Council of the ancients.
\v 16 Sephim, and Hosa toward the West, by the gate which leadeth to the way of ascent: watch against watch.
\v 17 And toward the East six Levites: and toward the North four a day: and toward the South likewise in a day four: and where the Council was, two and two.
\v 18 In the cells also of the porters toward the West four in the way: and two at every cell.
\v 19 These be the divisions of the porters of the sons of Core, and of Merari.
\v 20 Moreover Achias was over the treasures of the house of God, and the vessels of the holy places.
\v 21 The sons also of Ledan, the sons of Gersonni: of Ledan princes of the families, Ledan, and Gersonni, Jehieli.
\v 22 The sons of Jehieli: Zathan, and Joel, his brethren over the treasures of the house of our Lord,
\v 23 to the Amramites, and Isaarites, and Hebronites, and Ozielites.
\v 24 And Subael the son of Gersom, the son of Moyses, chief over the treasures.
\v 25 His brethren also Eliezer, whose son Rahabia, and his son Isaias, and his son Joram, his son also Zechri, and his son Selemith.
\v 26 Selemith himself, and his brethren over the treasures of the sanctified holy things, which David the king sanctified, and the Princes of families, and the centurions, and the captains of the host \f + \fr 26:26 \ft Things are sanctified by designation to holy use.\f*
\v 27 of the wars, and of the spoils of the battles, which they had consecrated to the maintenance and furniture of the temple of our Lord.
\v 28 And all these things did Samuel the Seer sanctify, and Saul the son of Cis, and Abner the son of Ner, and Joab the son of Sarvia: and all that had sanctified them by the hand of Selemith, and of his brethren.
\v 29 But the chief over the Isaarites was Chonenias, and his sons, to the works abroad over Israel, to teach and judge them.
\v 30 Moreover the Hebronites Hasabias, and his brethren most able men, a thousand seven hundred were chief over Israel beyond Jordan against the West, in all the works of our Lord, & for the ministry of the king.
\v 31 And the Prince of the Hebronites was Jeria according to their families and kindreds. In the fortieth year of king David they were numbered, and there were found most valiant men in Jazer Galaad,
\v 32 and his brethren of stronger age, two thousand seven hundred Princes of families. And David the king made them overseers over the Rubenites and the Gaddites, and the half tribe of Manasses, for all the ministry of God, and the king.
\c 27
\p
\v 1 And the children of Israel according to their number, the Princes of families, tribunes, and centurions, and overseers, that ministered to the king according to their companies, coming in and going out every month in the year, every one was chief over four and twenty thousand.
\v 2 Over the first company the first month Jesboam was chief the son of Zabdiel, and under him four & twenty thousand.
\v 3 Of the sons of Phares, the Prince of all the Princes in the host the first month.
\v 4 The company of the second month had Dudia an Ahohite, & after him another named Macelloth, which governed part of four and twenty thousand.
\v 5 Captain also of the third company in the third month, was Banaias the son of Joiada the Priest: and in his division four and twenty thousand.
\v 6 The same is Banaias the most valiant among thirty, and above the thirty, and over his company Amizabad his son was chief.
\v 7 The fourth, in the fourth month, Asahel the brother of Joab, and Zabadias his son after him: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 8 The fifth, in the fifth month, Prince Samaoth, a Jezerite: and his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 9 The sixth, in the sixth month, Hira the son of Acces a Thecuite: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 10 The seventh, in the seventh month, Helles a Phallonite of the children of Ephraim: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 11 The eight, in the eighth month, Sobochai an Husathite of the stock of Sarahi: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 12 The ninth, in the ninth month, Abiezer an Anathothite of the children of Jemini: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 13 The tenth, in the tenth month, Marai, & he a Netophathite of the stock of Zarahi: & in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 14 The eleventh in the eleventh month, Banaias, a Pharathonite of the children of Ephraim: & in his company four & twenty thousand.
\v 15 The twelfth, in the twelfth month, Holdai a Netophathite, of the stock of Gothoniel: and in his company four and twenty thousand.
\v 16 Furthermore there were chief over the tribes of Israel, over the Rubenites, Duke Eliezer the son of Zechri: over the Simeonites, Duke Saphatias the son of Maacha:
\v 17 over the Levites, Hasabias the son of Camuel: over the Aaronites, Sadoc:
\v 18 over Juda, Eliu the brother of David: over Issachar, Amri the son of Michael:
\v 19 over the Zabulonites, Jesmaias the son of Abdias: over the Nephthalites, Jerimoth the son of Ozriel:
\v 20 over the children of Ephraim, Osee the son of Ozaziu: over the half tribe of Manasses, Joel the son of Phadaia:
\v 21 and over the half tribe of Manasses in Galaad, Jaddo the son of Zacharias: and over Benjamin, Jasiel the son of Abner.
\v 22 But over Dan, Ezrihel the son of Jeroham: these be the Princes of the children of Israel.
\v 23 And David would not number them from twenty years downward: because our Lord had said that he would multiply Israel as the stars of heaven. \f + \fr 27:23 \ft King David having heretofore offended in commanding to number the whole people, 2. Reg. 24. would not now attempt to number all (which were indeed innumerable, but only those that were to be disposed of in special services.\f*
\v 24 Joab the son of Sarvia began to number, and finished not: because upon this there fell wrath upon Israel: and therefore the number of them that were numbered, was not registered in the chronicles of king David.
\v 25 And over the king's treasures was Azmoth the son of Adiel, and over those treasures, which were in the cities, and in the towns, and in the towers, Jonathan the son of Ozias was president.
\v 26 And over husbandry, and the husbandmen, which tilled the ground, Ezri the son of Chelub was overseer:
\v 27 and over the dressers of vineyards, Semeias a Romathite: and over the wine cellars, Zabdias an Aphonite.
\v 28 For over the Olivets and the fig-groves, which were in the champion, was Balanam a Gederite: and over the oil cellars, Joas.
\v 29 Furthermore over the herds that fed in Saron, the overseer was Setrai a Saronite: and over the oxen in the valleys, Saphat the son of Adli:
\v 30 but over the camels, Ubil an Ismaelite: and over the asses, Jadias a Meronathite:
\v 31 over the sheep also Jaziz an Agarene. All these, Princes of the substance of king David.
\v 32 And Jonathan David's uncle, a counsellor, a man wise and learned: He and Jahiel the son of Hachamoni were with the king's sons.
\v 33 Achitophel also the king's counsellor, and Chusai an Arachite the king's friend.
\v 34 After Achitophel was Joiada the son of Banaias, and Abiathar. And the Prince of the king's army was Joab.
\c 28
\p
to serve God sincerely: 10. and to build the temple, \add describing in what form to make it.\add*
\v 1 David therefore called together all the Princes of Israel, the Dukes of the tribes, and the heads of the companies, which ministered to the king: the tribunes also and the centurions, and them that were chief over the substance and possessions of the king, and his sons with the eunuchs, and the mighty, and all the most valiant in the host of Jerusalem. \x + \xo 28:1 \xt 3. Reg. 1.\x*
\v 2 And when the king had risen up, and stood, he said: Hear me my brethren, and my people: I meant to have built a house, wherein the Ark of our Lord might rest, and the foot stool of the feet of our God: and to build it I prepared all things.
\v 3 But God said to me: Thou shalt not build a house to my name: because thou art a man of war, and hast shed blood. \x + \xo 28:3 \xt 2. Reg. 7.\x*
\v 4 Howbeit our Lord the God of Israel chose me of all the house of my father, to be king over Israel for ever: for of Juda he chose the Princes: moreover of the house of Juda, my father's house: and of the sons of my father, it pleased him to choose me king over all Israel. \f + \fr 28:4 \ft So Jacob prophesied, that the royal sceptre should come to the tribe of Juda, & therein remain till Christ. Gen. 49.\f*
\v 5 Yea and of my sons (for our Lord hath given me many sons) he hath chosen Salomon my son, to sit in the throne of the Kingdom of our Lord over Israel,
\v 6 and he said to me: Salomon thy son shall build my house, and my courts: for him have I chosen to me for a son, and I will be to him for a father.
\v 7 And I will confirm his Kingdom for ever, if he shall persevere to do my precepts, and my judgments, as at this day. \f + \fr 28:7 \ft It is here evident, that Salomon was sometime the true servant and child of God, keeping his precepts & as certain, that he fell into great sins, & lost God's grace, & finally it is doubtful in what state he died. 3. Reg. 11. whereby is convinced their vain fancy that think, he who is once the child of God can never fall, nor become a wicked man.\f*
\v 8 Now then before all the assembly of Israel in the hearing of our God, keep ye, and search all the commandments of our Lord God: that you may possess the good land, & may leave it to your children after you for ever.
\v 9 And thou Salomon my son, know the God of thy father, and serve him with a perfect heart, and a voluntary mind: for our Lord searcheth all hearts, and understandeth all cogitations of minds. If thou seek him, thou shalt find: but if thou forsake him he will reject thee for ever.
\v 10 Now therefore because our Lord hath chosen thee to build the house of the Sanctuary, take courage, and perfit it.
\v 11 And David gave to Salomon his son a description of the porch, and of the temple and of the cellars, and of the upper loft, and of the chambers in the inner rooms, and of the house of the propitiation,
\v 12 moreover also of all the courts, which he had thought upon, and of the chambers round about, for the treasures of the house of our Lord, and for the treasures of the holy things,
\v 13 and of the divisions of the Priests and the Levites, for all the works of the house of our Lord, and for all the vessels of the ministry of the temple of our Lord.
\v 14 Gold in weight for every vessel of the ministry. A weight of silver also according to the diversity of the vessels and works.
\v 15 And for golden candlesticks also, and their lamps, gold according to the measure of every candlestick, and of the lamps. In like manner also for the silver candlesticks, and for their lamps, according to the diversity of the measure, he delivered a weight of silver.
\v 16 He gave also gold for tables of proposition, according to the diversity of the tables: in like manner also silver for other silver tables.
\v 17 For flesh-hooks also, and phials, and censers of most pure gold, and for little lions of gold, according to the quality of the measure he distributed a weight, for lion and lion. In like manner also for lions of silver he separated a diverse weight of silver.
\v 18 And for the Altar whereupon incense is burnt, he gave most pure gold: that of it might be made a similitude of the chariot of the Cherubs spreading their wings, and covering the Ark of the covenant of our Lord.
\v 19 All things, quoth he, came written with the hand of our Lord unto me: that I might understand all the works of the pattern.
\v 20 David also said to Salomon his son: Deal manfully, and take courage, and do it: fear not, and be not dismayed: for our Lord my God will be with thee, and will not leave thee, nor forsake thee, till thou perfit all the work of the ministry of the house of our Lord.
\v 21 Behold the divisions of the Priests and the Levites, for every ministry of the house of our Lord, assist thee, and are ready, and as well the Princes know, as the people, to do all thy precepts.
\c 29
\p
\v 1 And David the king spake to all the assembly: Salomon my son alone hath God chosen, as yet a child and a little tender one: for the work is great, neither is the habitation prepared for man, but for God.
\v 2 And I with all my ability have prepared the expenses of the house of my God. Gold for vessels of gold, and silver for them of silver, brass for them of brass, iron for them of iron, wood for them of wood: and onyx stones, and as it were stibians, and of diverse colours, and every precious stone, and marble of Paros most abundantly: \f + \fr 29:2 \ft * a kind of fine white stone.\f*
\v 3 and above these things, which I have offered into the house of my God, I give of mine own peculiar goods, gold & silver unto the temple of my God, beside those things, which I have prepared for the holy house: \f + \fr 29:3 \ft That which he had already vowed & prepared he counted not his own, and now giveth more to the building & furnishing of the Temple.\f*
\v 4 Three thousand talents of gold of the gold of Ophir: and seven thousand talents of most approved silver, to guilt the walls of the temple.
\v 5 And wheresoever there needeth gold, of gold: and wheresoever there needeth silver, of silver: let the works be made by the hands of the artificers: and if any man offer voluntarily, let him fill his hand today, and offer what he will to our Lord.
\v 6 The Princes therefore of the families promised, and the nobles of the tribes of Israel, the tribunes also and the centurions, and the Princes of the king's possessions.
\v 7 And they gave unto the works of the house of our Lord, of gold, five thousand talents, and ten thousand solidos: of silver ten thousand talents, and of brass eighteen thousand talents: of iron also an hundred thousand talents.
\v 8 And with whomsoever were found stones, they gave them into the treasures of the house of our Lord, by the hand of Jahiel the Gersonite.
\v 9 And the people rejoiced, when they promised vows of their own accord: because they did offer them to our Lord with all their heart: yea and David the king rejoiced with great joy.
\v 10 And he blessed our Lord before all the multitude, and he said: Blessed art thou, o Lord the God of Israel, our father, from eternity unto eternity.
\v 11 Thine o Lord is the magnificence, and might, and glory, and victory: and to thee is the praise: for all things that be in heaven, and in the earth, are thine: thine o Lord is the Kingdom, & thou art over all Princes.
\v 12 Thine are riches and thine is glory: thou hast dominion over all, in thy hand is power and might: in thy hand greatness, and the empire of all things.
\v 13 Now therefore our God we confess to thee, and we praise thy glorious name.
\v 14 Who am I, and what is my people, that we can promise thee all these things? All are thine: and things that we received of thy hand, we have given thee.
\v 15 For we are pilgrims before thee, and strangers, as all our fathers. Our days are as a shadow upon the earth, and there is no abiding. \f + \fr 29:15 \ft As Abraham, Isaac, Jacob & others were strangers in respect of Chanaan: so both they, and also David, Salomon, and all men in this world, are pilgrims in respect of heaven. Heb. 13.\f*
\v 16 Lord our God, all this plenty, which we have prepared that a house might be built to thy holy name, is of thy hand, and all things are thine.
\v 17 I know my God that thou provest the hearts, and lovest simplicity, wherefore I also in the simplicity of my heart, gladly have offered all these things: and thy people, which is here found, I have seen with great joy offer thee donaries.
\v 18 Lord God of Abraham, and Isaac, and Israel our fathers, keep for ever this will of their heart, and let this mind remain always to the honour of thee.
\v 19 To Salomon also my son give a perfect heart, that he keep thy commandments, thy testimonies, and thy ceremonies, and do all things: and build the house, the expenses whereof I have prepared.
\v 20 And David commanded the whole assembly: Bless ye our Lord God. And all the assembly blessed our Lord the God of their fathers: and they bowed themselves, & adored God, and then the king. \f + \fr 29:20 \ft Albeit they did the same exterior act of honour to God and the King: yet in their mind and intention they gave divine honour to God, and civil to the King. See Exod. 20.\f*
\v 21 And they immolated victim to our Lord: and they offered holocausts the day following, oxen a thousand, rams a thousand, lambs a thousand with their libaments, and with all rite most aboundantly for all Israel.
\v 22 And they did eat, and drink before our Lord in that day with great joy. And they anointed the second time Salomon the son of David. And they anointed him to our Lord for the Prince, and Sadoc for the high Priest. \x + \xo 29:22 \xt 3. Reg. 1. v. 34.\x*
\v 23 And Salomon sat upon the throne of our Lord as king for David his father, and he pleased all: and all Israel obeyed him.
\v 24 Yea and all the princes, and men of might, and all the sons of king David gave their hand, and were subject to Salomon the king.
\v 25 Our Lord therefore magnified Salomon over all Israel: & gave him the glory of a Kingdom, such as no king of Israel had before him.
\v 26 David therefore the son of Isai reigned over all Israel.
\v 27 And the days that he reigned over Israel, were forty years: in Hebron he reigned seven years, and in Jerusalem three & thirty years.
\v 28 And he died in a good old age, full of days, and riches, & glory. And Salomon his son reigned for him.
\v 29 But the acts of king David the first and the last are written in the Book of Samuel the Seer, and in the Book of Nathan the Prophet, and in the Volume of Gad the Seer: \f + \fr 29:29 \ft Either Nathan and Gad writ the later part of the first book, and the second book of Kings, or else their books are not now extant.\f*
\v 30 and of all his Kingdom, and strength, and of the times, that passed under him, either in Israel, or in all the Kingdoms of the earth.
